{"title_page": "Moraes Moreira", "text_new": "{{short description|Brazilian singer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = \n| background = solo_singer\n| image = Morais_Moreira_cropped.jpg\n| image_size = 250\n| birth_name = Ant\u00f4nio Carlos Moreira Pires\n| birth_date = {{Birth date |1947|7|8}}\n| birth_place = [[Itua\u00e7u|Itua\u00e7u, Bahia]], Brazil\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|2020|4|13|1947|7|18}}\n| death_place = [[Rio de Janeiro|Rio de Janeiro, Rio de Janeiro]], Brazil\n| genre = {{hlist|[[M\u00fasica popular brasileira|MPB]]|[[frevo]]|[[samba]]|[[ijex\u00e1]]}}\n| instrument = {{hlist|Vocals|guitar}}\n| years_active = 1969\u20132020\n| label = {{hlist|[[Continental (label)|Continental]]|[[Ariola Discos]]|[[Barclay Discos]]|[[Discos CBS]]|[[Universal Music]]|[[Sony Music]]|[[Warner Music]]}}\n| associated_acts = [[Novos Baianos]]\n}}\n\n'''Ant\u00f4nio Carlos Moreira Pires''' (July 8, 1947 \u2013 April 13, 2020), better known as '''Moraes Moreira''', was a [[Brazilians|Brazilian]] musician and singer.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://rollingstone.uol.com.br/listas/100-maiores-vozes-da-musica-brasileira/moraes-moreira/|title=Listas - As 100 Maiores Vozes da M\u00fasica Brasileira - Moraes Moreira - Rolling Stone Brasil|access-date=May 3, 2017|language=pt|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180912201727/http://rollingstone.uol.com.br/listas/100-maiores-vozes-da-musica-brasileira/moraes-moreira|archive-date=September 12, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> During the 1970s he played guitar and sang in the band [[Os Novos Baianos]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=65X-CwAAQBAJ&pg=PA88&dq=morais+moreira+novos&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwin2_GqkdTTAhUCw4MKHchgCngQ6AEITjAI#v=onepage&q=morais%20moreira%20novos&f=false|title=Contracultura: Alternative Arts and Social Transformation in Authoritarian Brazil|last=Dunn|first=Christopher|date=October 13, 2016|publisher=UNC Press Books|isbn=9781469628523|language=en}}</ref> After playing in [[Novos Baianos|Os Novos Baianos]], Moreira embarked on a solo career where he recorded 29 albums.<ref name=\"Pereira2010\">Pereira, Ian\u00e1 Souza. Ax\u00e9-ax\u00e9: o megafen\u00f4meno baiano. Revista \u00c1frica e Africanidades, Rio de Janeiro, ano 2, n. 8, February 2010, p.02</ref> Moreira was involved in recording 40 full-length albums between Os Novos Baianos, Trio El\u00e9trico Dod\u00f4 e Osmar, and two more albums with guitarist Pepeu Gomes. Moreira was considered one of the most versatile composers of Brazil, mixing the genres of rock, [[samba]], ''choro'', ''frevo'', ''[[Bai\u00e3o (music)|bai\u00e3o]]'', and classical.\n\n==Career==\n\n===Novos Baianos===\nMoreira began playing accordion in festivals at S\u00e3o Jo\u00e3o and other events in Itua\u00e7u, Brazil such as \"Portal da Chapada Diamantina\". In his youth he learned to play the classical guitar while taking a science class in Cacul\u00e9, Bahia, Brazil. He moved to Salvador and there met Tom Z\u00e9, and was also introduced to rock music. On meeting [[Baby Consuelo]], [[Pepeu Gomes]], [[Paulinho Boca de Cantor]], and [[Luiz Galv\u00e3o]], they formed the band os Novos Baianos, and were active from 1969 until 1975.<ref name=\"Morre Moraes Moreira, o eterno novo baiano\">{{cite web |last1=Oliveira |first1=Joana |title=Morre Moraes Moreira, o eterno novo baiano |url=https://brasil.elpais.com/cultura/2020-04-13/morre-moraes-moreira-o-eterno-novo-baiano.html |website=[[El Pa\u00eds]] |accessdate=14 April 2020 |language=Portuguese}}</ref> Together with [[Pepeu Gomes]], he composed almost all of the songs of the group. The album ''[[Acabou Chorare]]'', released by the band in 1972, has been ranked by Rolling Stone Brasil as the greatest Brazilian music album of all time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://rollingstone.uol.com.br/galeria/os-100-maiores-discos-da-musica-brasileira/#imagem2|title=Listas - os-100-maiores-discos-da-musica-brasileira - Rolling Stone Brasil|access-date=May 20, 2017|language=pt}}</ref>\n\n===Solo career===\nMoraes began his solo career in 1975, and has since then recorded more than 20 albums. In his solo career, he was the lead singer in the trio Trio de Dod\u00f4 e Osmar, and recorded many popular songs associated with [[Brazilian Carnival]], in what was conventionally called \"frevo trieletrizado\". Some of the hits during this part of his career include, \"Pombo Correio\", \"Vassourinha El\u00e9trica\", and \"Bloco do Prazer\".<ref name=\"Morre Moraes Moreira, o eterno novo baiano\" /><ref name=\"Moraes Moreira foi pe\u00e7a-chave para o sucesso do Carnaval da Bahia\">{{cite web |last1=Baltar |first1=Anderson |title=Moraes Moreira foi pe\u00e7a-chave para o sucesso do Carnaval da Bahia |url=https://entretenimento.uol.com.br/noticias/redacao/2020/04/13/moraes-moreira-foi-peca-chave-para-o-sucesso-do-carnaval-da-bahia.htm |website=UOL |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 1980s he distanced himself from the [[Bahian Carnival]] due to increasing commercialization from tourism. In 1994 he recorded \"Brasil Tem Concerto\" which was influenced by classical music, and in the following year appeared in the MTV special \"Moraes Moreira Ac\u00fastico MTV\" which was later released as a CD and DVD. In 1997, he recorded \"50 Carnavais\" which commemorated his 50th birthday and 50 carnivals. Two years later, he recorded \"500 Sambas\" em homenagem aos 500 anos de descobrimento do Brasil which focused on [[samba]] music.<ref name=\"Relembre os maiores sucessos da carreira de Moraes Moreira\">{{cite web |title=Relembre os maiores sucessos da carreira de Moraes Moreira |url=https://www.ibahia.com/entretenimento/detalhe/noticia/relembre-os-maiores-sucessos-da-carreira-de-moraes-moreira/ |website=iBahia |accessdate=14 April 2020 |language=Portuguese}}</ref><ref name=\"Moraes Moreira - Enciclop\u00e9dia It\u00e1u Cultural\">{{cite web |title=Moraes Moreira |url=http://enciclopedia.itaucultural.org.br/pessoa15192/moraes-moreira |website=Enciclop\u00e9dia It\u00e1u Cultural |accessdate=14 April 2020 |language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, he released \"Bahi\u00e3o com H\", playing [[Bai\u00e3o (music)|bai\u00e3o]] with characteristic Bahian rhythms. In 2003, with the release of \"Meu Nome \u00e9 Brasil (2003)\", he completed his Brazil's themed trilogy, which, also, included \"L\u00e1 Vem o Brasil Descendo a Ladeira\" (1979) and \"O Brasil Tem Concerto\" (1994).<ref name=\"Moraes Moreira - Dicion\u00e1rio Cravo Albin da M\u00fasica Popular Brasileira\">{{cite web |title=Moraes Moreira |url=http://dicionariompb.com.br/moraes-moreira/discografia |website=Dicion\u00e1rio Cravo Albin da M\u00fasica Popular Brasileira |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> In 2005, he independently released the album \"De Repente\", which mixed [[hip hop]] with [[Northeastern Brazil|Northeastern Brazilian]] influences and included his characteristic classical guitar swing rhythms.<ref name=\"Moraes Moreira: dez fatos que voc\u00ea (provavelmente) n\u00e3o sabia sobre o cantor\" /> He published the book, \"A hist\u00f3ria dos Novos Baianos e outros versos\" (The History of the Novos Baianos and other verses), in which he told the history of the group in a [[chapbook]] and interesting aspects of his solo career.<ref name=\"Moraes Moreira: dez fatos que voc\u00ea (provavelmente) n\u00e3o sabia sobre o cantor\">{{cite web |title=Moraes Moreira: dez fatos que voc\u00ea (provavelmente) n\u00e3o sabia sobre o cantor |url=https://entretenimento.uol.com.br/noticias/redacao/2020/04/13/moraes-moreira-dez-fatos-que-voce-provavelmente-nao-sabia-sobre-o-cantor.htm |website=UOL |accessdate=14 April 2020 |language=Portuguese}}</ref> The book resulted in a Brazilian tour of the same name where he played his major hits and recited passages from the book. In 2009, it was released as a DVD and CD. In 2012, he recorded the album ''A Revolta dos Ritmos'', a compilation of 12 of his unedited recordings.<ref name=\"Morre o cantor e compositor Moraes Moreira\">{{cite web |title=Morre o cantor e compositor Moraes Moreira |url=https://www.bemparana.com.br/noticia/morre-o-cantor-e-compositor-moraes-moreira-integrantes-dos-novos-baianos#.XpUKYmZv_IU |website=Bem Paran\u00e1 |accessdate=14 April 2020 |language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nMoreira died on April 13, 2020, at age 72.<ref>{{cite news|url = https://jornaldebrasilia.com.br/clica-brasilia/morre-o-cantor-e-compositor-moraes-moreira/|title = Morre o cantor e compositor Moraes Moreira|work = Jornal de Bras\u00edlia|date = April 13, 2020|accessdate = April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Solo discography==\n<small>Source:</small><ref name=\"Moraes Moreira - Dicion\u00e1rio Cravo Albin da M\u00fasica Popular Brasileira\" />\n{{div col}}\n* 1975 \u2013 Moraes Moreira (Som Livre)\n* 1977 \u2013 Cara e Cora\u00e7\u00e3o (Som Livre)\n* 1978 \u2013 Alto Falante (Som Livre)\n* 1979 \u2013 L\u00e1 vem o Brasil Descendo a Ladeira (Som Livre)\n* 1980 \u2013 Bazar Brasileiro (Ariola)\n* 1981 \u2013 Moraes Moreira (Ariola)\n* 1983 \u2013 Coisa Acesa (Ariola)\n* 1983 \u2013 Pintando o Oito (Ariola)\n* 1984 \u2013 Mancha de Dend\u00ea N\u00e3o Sai (Ariola)\n* 1985 \u2013 Tocando a Vida (CBS)\n* 1986 \u2013 Mesti\u00e7o \u00e9 Isso (CBS)\n* 1988 \u2013 Rep\u00fablica da M\u00fasica (CBS)\n* 1988 \u2013 Baiano Fala Cantando (CBS)\n* 1990 \u2013 Moraes e Pepeu (Warner)\n* 1994 \u2013 Moraes e Pepeu - Ao vivo no Jap\u00e3o (Warner)\n* 1991 \u2013 Cidad\u00e3o (Sony)\n* 1993 \u2013 Terreiro do Mundo (Polygram)\n* 1993 \u2013 Tem um P\u00e9 no Pel\u00f4 (Som Livre)\n* 1994 \u2013 O Brasil tem Conserto (Polygram)\n* 1995 \u2013 Moraes Moreira Ac\u00fastico MTV (EMI-Odeon)\n* 1996 \u2013 Estados (Virgin)\n* 1997 \u2013 50 Carnavais (Virgin)\n* 1999 \u2013 500 Sambas (Abril Music)\n* 2000 \u2013 Bahi\u00e3o com H (Atra\u00e7\u00e3o Fonogr\u00e1fica)\n* 2003 \u2013 Meu Nome \u00e9 Brasil (Universal)\n* 2005 \u2013 De Repente (Rob Digital)\n* 2009 \u2013 A Hist\u00f3ria dos Novos Baianos e Outros Versos (Biscoito Fino)\n* 2012 \u2013 A Revolta dos Ritmos (Biscoito Fino)\n* 2018 \u2013 Ser T\u00e3o (Discobertas)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://moraesmoreira.com.br Official site] (in Portuguese)\n* [https://www.facebook.com/moraesmoreiraoficial Moraes Moreira on Facebook]\n* [http://dicionariompb.com.br/moraes-moreira/biografia Moraes Moreira on] [[Dicion\u00e1rio Cravo Albin da M\u00fasica Popular Brasileira]] (in Portuguese)\n* [http://www.allmusic.com/artist/moraes-moreira-mn0000927926 Moraes Moreira on Allmusic]\n* {{Discogs artist|Moraes Moreira}}\n* [http://www.folderpark.net/moraes-moreira/ Moraes Moreira in the 80s] (in English and Portuguese)\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moreira, Moraes}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Brazilian musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Brazilian musicians]]\n[[Category:Brazilian guitarists]]\n[[Category:Brazilian male singers]]\n[[Category:People from Bahia]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Brazilian singer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = \n| background = solo_singer\n| image = Morais_Moreira_cropped.jpg\n| image_size = 250\n| birth_name = Ant\u00f4nio Carlos Moreira Pires\n| birth_date = {{Birth date |1947|7|8}}\n| birth_place = [[Itua\u00e7u|Itua\u00e7u, Bahia]], Brazil\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|2020|4|13|1947|7|18}}\n| death_place = [[Rio de Janeiro|Rio de Janeiro, Rio de Janeiro]], Brazil\n| genre = {{hlist|[[M\u00fasica popular brasileira|MPB]]|[[frevo]]|[[samba]]|[[ijex\u00e1]]}}\n| instrument = {{hlist|Vocals|guitar}}\n| years_active = 1969\u20132020\n| label = {{hlist|[[Continental (label)|Continental]]|[[Ariola Discos]]|[[Barclay Discos]]|[[Discos CBS]]|[[Universal Music]]|[[Sony Music]]|[[Warner Music]]}}\n| associated_acts = [[Novos Baianos]]\n}}\n\n'''Ant\u00f4nio Carlos Moreira Pires''' (July 8, 1947 \u2013 April 13, 2020), better known as '''Moraes Moreira''', was a [[Brazilians|Brazilian]] musician and singer.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://rollingstone.uol.com.br/listas/100-maiores-vozes-da-musica-brasileira/moraes-moreira/|title=Listas - As 100 Maiores Vozes da M\u00fasica Brasileira - Moraes Moreira - Rolling Stone Brasil|access-date=May 3, 2017|language=pt|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180912201727/http://rollingstone.uol.com.br/listas/100-maiores-vozes-da-musica-brasileira/moraes-moreira|archive-date=September 12, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> During the 1970s he played guitar and sang in the band [[Os Novos Baianos]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=65X-CwAAQBAJ&pg=PA88&dq=morais+moreira+novos&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwin2_GqkdTTAhUCw4MKHchgCngQ6AEITjAI#v=onepage&q=morais%20moreira%20novos&f=false|title=Contracultura: Alternative Arts and Social Transformation in Authoritarian Brazil|last=Dunn|first=Christopher|date=October 13, 2016|publisher=UNC Press Books|isbn=9781469628523|language=en}}</ref> After playing in [[Novos Baianos|Os Novos Baianos]], Moreira embarked on a solo career where he recorded 29 albums.<ref name=\"Pereira2010\">Pereira, Ian\u00e1 Souza. Ax\u00e9-ax\u00e9: o megafen\u00f4meno baiano. Revista \u00c1frica e Africanidades, Rio de Janeiro, ano 2, n. 8, February 2010, p.02</ref> Moreira was involved in recording 40 full-length albums between Os Novos Baianos, Trio El\u00e9trico Dod\u00f4 e Osmar, and two more albums with guitarist Pepeu Gomes. Moreira was considered one of the most versatile composers of Brazil, mixing the genres of rock, [[samba]], ''choro'', ''frevo'', ''[[Bai\u00e3o (music)|bai\u00e3o]]'', and classical.\n\n==Career==\n\n===Novos Baianos===\nMoreira began playing accordion in festivals at S\u00e3o Jo\u00e3o and other events in Itua\u00e7u, Brazil such as \"Portal da Chapada Diamantina\". In his youth he learned to play the classical guitar while taking a science class in Cacul\u00e9, Bahia, Brazil. He moved to Salvador and there met Tom Z\u00e9, and was also introduced to rock music. On meeting [[Baby Consuelo]], [[Pepeu Gomes]], [[Paulinho Boca de Cantor]], and [[Luiz Galv\u00e3o]], they formed the band os Novos Baianos, and were active from 1969 until 1975.<ref name=\"Morre Moraes Moreira, o eterno novo baiano\">{{cite web |last1=Oliveira |first1=Joana |title=Morre Moraes Moreira, o eterno novo baiano |url=https://brasil.elpais.com/cultura/2020-04-13/morre-moraes-moreira-o-eterno-novo-baiano.html |website=[[El Pa\u00eds]] |accessdate=14 April 2020 |language=Portuguese}}</ref> Together with [[Pepeu Gomes]], he composed almost all of the songs of the group. The album ''[[Acabou Chorare]]'', released by the band in 1972, has been ranked by Rolling Stone Brasil as the greatest Brazilian music album of all time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://rollingstone.uol.com.br/galeria/os-100-maiores-discos-da-musica-brasileira/#imagem2|title=Listas - os-100-maiores-discos-da-musica-brasileira - Rolling Stone Brasil|access-date=May 20, 2017|language=pt}}</ref>\n\n===Solo career===\nMoraes began his solo career in 1975, and has since then recorded more than 20 albums. In his solo career, he was the lead singer in the trio Trio de Dod\u00f4 e Osmar, and recorded many popular songs associated with [[Brazilian Carnival]], in what was conventionally called \"frevo trieletrizado\". Some of the hits during this part of his career include, \"Pombo Correio\", \"Vassourinha El\u00e9trica\", and \"Bloco do Prazer\".<ref name=\"Morre Moraes Moreira, o eterno novo baiano\" /><ref name=\"Moraes Moreira foi pe\u00e7a-chave para o sucesso do Carnaval da Bahia\">{{cite web |last1=Baltar |first1=Anderson |title=Moraes Moreira foi pe\u00e7a-chave para o sucesso do Carnaval da Bahia |url=https://entretenimento.uol.com.br/noticias/redacao/2020/04/13/moraes-moreira-foi-peca-chave-para-o-sucesso-do-carnaval-da-bahia.htm |website=UOL |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 1980s he distanced himself from the [[Bahian Carnival]] due to increasing commercialization from tourism. In 1994 he recorded \"Brasil Tem Concerto\" which was influenced by classical music, and in the following year appeared in the MTV special \"Moraes Moreira Ac\u00fastico MTV\" which was later released as a CD and DVD. In 1997, he recorded \"50 Carnavais\" which commemorated his 50th birthday and 50 carnivals. Two years later, he recorded \"500 Sambas\" em homenagem aos 500 anos de descobrimento do Brasil which focused on [[samba]] music.<ref name=\"Relembre os maiores sucessos da carreira de Moraes Moreira\">{{cite web |title=Relembre os maiores sucessos da carreira de Moraes Moreira |url=https://www.ibahia.com/entretenimento/detalhe/noticia/relembre-os-maiores-sucessos-da-carreira-de-moraes-moreira/ |website=iBahia |accessdate=14 April 2020 |language=Portuguese}}</ref><ref name=\"Moraes Moreira - Enciclop\u00e9dia It\u00e1u Cultural\">{{cite web |title=Moraes Moreira |url=http://enciclopedia.itaucultural.org.br/pessoa15192/moraes-moreira |website=Enciclop\u00e9dia It\u00e1u Cultural |accessdate=14 April 2020 |language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, he released \"Bahi\u00e3o com H\", playing [[Bai\u00e3o (music)|bai\u00e3o]] with characteristic Bahian rhythms. In 2003, with the release of \"Meu Nome \u00e9 Brasil (2003)\", he completed his Brazil's themed trilogy, which, also, included \"L\u00e1 Vem o Brasil Descendo a Ladeira\" (1979) and \"O Brasil Tem Concerto\" (1994).<ref name=\"Moraes Moreira - Dicion\u00e1rio Cravo Albin da M\u00fasica Popular Brasileira\">{{cite web |title=Moraes Moreira |url=http://dicionariompb.com.br/moraes-moreira/discografia |website=Dicion\u00e1rio Cravo Albin da M\u00fasica Popular Brasileira |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> In 2005, he independently released the album \"De Repente\", which mixed [[hip hop]] with [[Northeastern Brazil|Northeastern Brazilian]] influences and included his characteristic classical guitar swing rhythms.<ref name=\"Moraes Moreira: dez fatos que voc\u00ea (provavelmente) n\u00e3o sabia sobre o cantor\" /> He published the book, \"A hist\u00f3ria dos Novos Baianos e outros versos\" (The History of the Novos Baianos and other verses), in which he told the history of the group in a [[chapbook]] and interesting aspects of his solo career.<ref name=\"Moraes Moreira: dez fatos que voc\u00ea (provavelmente) n\u00e3o sabia sobre o cantor\">{{cite web |title=Moraes Moreira: dez fatos que voc\u00ea (provavelmente) n\u00e3o sabia sobre o cantor |url=https://entretenimento.uol.com.br/noticias/redacao/2020/04/13/moraes-moreira-dez-fatos-que-voce-provavelmente-nao-sabia-sobre-o-cantor.htm |website=UOL |accessdate=14 April 2020 |language=Portuguese}}</ref> The book resulted in a Brazilian tour of the same name where he played his major hits and recited passages from the book. In 2009, it was released as a DVD and CD. In 2012, he recorded the album \"A Revolta dos Ritmos\", a compilation of 12 of his unedited recordings.<ref name=\"Morre o cantor e compositor Moraes Moreira\">{{cite web |title=Morre o cantor e compositor Moraes Moreira |url=https://www.bemparana.com.br/noticia/morre-o-cantor-e-compositor-moraes-moreira-integrantes-dos-novos-baianos#.XpUKYmZv_IU |website=Bem Paran\u00e1 |accessdate=14 April 2020 |language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nMoreira died on April 13, 2020, at age 72.<ref>{{cite news|url = https://jornaldebrasilia.com.br/clica-brasilia/morre-o-cantor-e-compositor-moraes-moreira/|title = Morre o cantor e compositor Moraes Moreira|work = Jornal de Bras\u00edlia|date = April 13, 2020|accessdate = April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Solo discography==\n<small>Source:</small><ref name=\"Moraes Moreira - Dicion\u00e1rio Cravo Albin da M\u00fasica Popular Brasileira\" />\n{{div col}}\n* 1975 \u2013 Moraes Moreira (Som Livre)\n* 1977 \u2013 Cara e Cora\u00e7\u00e3o (Som Livre)\n* 1978 \u2013 Alto Falante (Som Livre)\n* 1979 \u2013 L\u00e1 vem o Brasil Descendo a Ladeira (Som Livre)\n* 1980 \u2013 Bazar Brasileiro (Ariola)\n* 1981 \u2013 Moraes Moreira (Ariola)\n* 1983 \u2013 Coisa Acesa (Ariola)\n* 1983 \u2013 Pintando o Oito (Ariola)\n* 1984 \u2013 Mancha de Dend\u00ea N\u00e3o Sai (Ariola)\n* 1985 \u2013 Tocando a Vida (CBS)\n* 1986 \u2013 Mesti\u00e7o \u00e9 Isso (CBS)\n* 1988 \u2013 Rep\u00fablica da M\u00fasica (CBS)\n* 1988 \u2013 Baiano Fala Cantando (CBS)\n* 1990 \u2013 Moraes e Pepeu (Warner)\n* 1994 \u2013 Moraes e Pepeu - Ao vivo no Jap\u00e3o (Warner)\n* 1991 \u2013 Cidad\u00e3o (Sony)\n* 1993 \u2013 Terreiro do Mundo (Polygram)\n* 1993 \u2013 Tem um P\u00e9 no Pel\u00f4 (Som Livre)\n* 1994 \u2013 O Brasil tem Conserto (Polygram)\n* 1995 \u2013 Moraes Moreira Ac\u00fastico MTV (EMI-Odeon)\n* 1996 \u2013 Estados (Virgin)\n* 1997 \u2013 50 Carnavais (Virgin)\n* 1999 \u2013 500 Sambas (Abril Music)\n* 2000 \u2013 Bahi\u00e3o com H (Atra\u00e7\u00e3o Fonogr\u00e1fica)\n* 2003 \u2013 Meu Nome \u00e9 Brasil (Universal)\n* 2005 \u2013 De Repente (Rob Digital)\n* 2009 \u2013 A Hist\u00f3ria dos Novos Baianos e Outros Versos (Biscoito Fino)\n* 2012 \u2013 A Revolta dos Ritmos (Biscoito Fino)\n* 2018 \u2013 Ser T\u00e3o (Discobertas)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://moraesmoreira.com.br Official site] (in Portuguese)\n* [https://www.facebook.com/moraesmoreiraoficial Moraes Moreira on Facebook]\n* [http://dicionariompb.com.br/moraes-moreira/biografia Moraes Moreira on] [[Dicion\u00e1rio Cravo Albin da M\u00fasica Popular Brasileira]] (in Portuguese)\n* [http://www.allmusic.com/artist/moraes-moreira-mn0000927926 Moraes Moreira on Allmusic]\n* {{Discogs artist|Moraes Moreira}}\n* [http://www.folderpark.net/moraes-moreira/ Moraes Moreira in the 80s] (in English and Portuguese)\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moreira, Moraes}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Brazilian musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Brazilian musicians]]\n[[Category:Brazilian guitarists]]\n[