17/}}\n*{{IMDb name|0366389|Kevin Hart}}\n*{{Rotten Tomatoes person|kevin_hart}}\n*{{Twitter}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Pennsylvania|Philadelphia|Comedy|Television|Film|United States}}{{People's Choice Award for Favorite Cable TV Actor}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hart, Kevin}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American comedians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:African-American male actors]]\n[[Category:African-American male comedians]]\n[[Category:American male comedians]]\n[[Category:African-American stand-up comedians]]\n[[Category:American stand-up comedians]]\n[[Category:African-American television producers]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male voice actors]]\n[[Category:Television producers from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:American television writers]]\n[[Category:Community College of Philadelphia alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Male television writers]]\n[[Category:Comedians from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Film producers from Pennsylvania]]\n", "name_user": "75.108.147.140", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eCareer)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kevin_Hart"}
{"title_page": "Hitchcock (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2012 film by Sacha Gervasi}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Hitchcock\n| image          = Hitchcock film poster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Sacha Gervasi]]\n| producer       = [[Ivan Reitman]]<br>[[Tom Pollock]]<br>[[Joe Medjuck]]<br>Tom Thayer<br>Alan Barnette\n| screenplay     = John J. McLaughlin\n| based on       = {{based on|''[[Alfred Hitchcock and the Making of Psycho]]''|[[Stephen Rebello]]}}\n| starring       = [[Anthony Hopkins]]<br>[[Helen Mirren]]<br>[[Scarlett Johansson]]<br>[[Toni Collette]]<br>[[Danny Huston]]<br>[[Jessica Biel]]<br>[[James D'Arcy]]<br>[[Michael Wincott]]<!-- PER BILLING BLOCK -->\n| music          = [[Danny Elfman]]\n| cinematography = [[Jeff Cronenweth]]\n| editing        = [[Pamela Martin (film editor)|Pamela Martin]]\n| studio         = [[The Montecito Picture Company]]<br>Cold Spring Pictures<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/executive-suite-tom-pollock-ivan-165068 |title=Executive Suite: Tom Pollock and Ivan Reitman |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=2011-10-03 |accessdate=2014-01-25}}</ref> \n| distributor    = [[Searchlight Pictures|Fox Searchlight Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2012|11|01|[[AFI Fest]]|2012|11|23|United States}}\n| runtime        = 98 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 98:12--><ref>{{cite web|title=''HITCHCOCK'' (12A)|url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/AFF295678/|work=[[British Board of Film Classification]]|date=November 13, 2012|accessdate=2012-11-13}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $15 million<ref>https://www.screendaily.com/features/awards-countdown/hitchcock-psycho-path/5049543.article</ref>\n| gross          = $27 million<ref name=\"the-numbers.com\">http://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Hitchcock#tab=more Retrieved October 23, 2017.</ref> \n}}\n'''''Hitchcock''''' is a 2012 American [[Biographical film|biographical]] [[drama (film and television)|drama film]] directed by [[Sacha Gervasi]], based on [[Stephen Rebello]]'s non-fiction book ''[[Alfred Hitchcock and the Making of Psycho]]''. The film was released in selected cities on November 23, 2012,<ref name=\"HP\" /> with a worldwide release on December 14, 2012.\n\n''Hitchcock'' centers on the relationship between film director [[Alfred Hitchcock]] ([[Anthony Hopkins]]) and his wife [[Alma Reville]] ([[Helen Mirren]]) during the making of ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]'', a controversial [[horror film]] that became one of the most acclaimed and influential works in the filmmaker's career.\n\n==Plot ==\nIn 1959, Alfred Hitchcock opens his latest film, ''[[North by Northwest]]'', to both critical and commercial success, but is troubled by a reporter's insinuation that he should retire. Seeking to reclaim the artistic daring of his youth, Hitchcock turns down film proposals, including ''[[Casino Royale (novel)|Casino Royale]]'' and ''[[The Diary of Anne Frank (1959 film)|The Diary of Anne Frank]]'', in favor of a horror novel called ''[[Psycho (novel)|Psycho]]'' by [[Robert Bloch]],  based on the real-life crimes of murderer [[Ed Gein]]. Gein appears in sequences throughout the film, in which he seems to prompt Hitchcock's imagination regarding the ''Psycho'' story, or act as some function of Hitchcock's subconscious mind (for instance, drawing Hitchcock's attention to sand on his bathroom floor, the quantity of which reveals how much time his wife Alma has been spending at the beachhouse with Whitfield Cook).\n\nHitchcock's wife and artistic collaborator, Alma, is no more enthusiastic about the idea than his colleagues, especially since she is being lobbied by their writer friend, [[Whitfield Cook]], to look at his own screenplay. However, she warms to Hitchcock's proposal, suggesting the innovative plot turn of killing the female lead early in the film. The studio heads at [[Paramount Pictures|Paramount]] prove more difficult to persuade, forcing Hitchcock to finance the film personally and use his ''[[Alfred Hitchcock Presents]]'' television crew (over at competitor Revue/Universal) to shoot the film, his last with Paramount.\n\nHowever, the pressures of the production, such as dealing with Geoffrey Shurlock of the [[Motion Picture Production Code]], and Hitchcock's lecherous habits, such as when they confer with the female lead, [[Janet Leigh]], annoy Alma. She begins a personal writing collaboration with Whitfield Cook on his screenplay at his beach house without Hitchcock's knowledge. Hitchcock eventually discovers what she has been doing and suspects her of having an affair.  This concern affects Hitchcock's work on ''Psycho''. Hitchcock eventually confronts Alma and asks her if she is having an affair. Alma angrily denies it.\n\nAlma temporarily takes over production of the film when Hitchcock is bedridden after collapsing from overwork, but this sequence, which included a complicated [[Rear projection effect|process shot]] showing Detective Arbogast's demise, with Alma's specification of a 35mm lens, instead of the 50mm lens preferred by Hitchcock for this film, proved to be the least effective in the film.\n\nMeanwhile, Hitchcock expresses his disappointment to [[Vera Miles]] at how she didn't follow through on his plan to make her the next biggest star after [[Grace Kelly]], but Miles says she is happy with her family life.\n\nHitchcock's cut of ''Psycho'' is poorly received by the studio executives, while Alma discovers Whitfield having sex with a younger woman at his beach house. Hitchcock and Alma reconcile and set to work on improving the film. Their renewed collaboration yields results, culminating in Alma persuading Hitchcock to accept their composer's suggestion for adding [[Bernard Herrmann]]'s harsh strings score to the shower scene.\n\nAfter maneuvering Shurlock into leaving the film's content largely intact, Hitchcock learns the studio is only going to open the film in two theaters. Hitchcock arranges for special theater instructions to pique the public's interest such as forbidding admittance after the film begins. At the film's premiere, Hitchcock first views the audience from the projection booth, looking out through its small window at them. Hitchcock then waits in the lobby for the audience's reaction, conducting slashing motions to their reactions as they scream on cue. The film is rewarded with an enthusiastic reception.\n\nWith the film's screening so well received, Hitchcock publicly thanks his wife for helping make it possible and they affirm their love and partnership. At the conclusion at his home, Hitchcock addresses the audience noting ''Psycho'' proved a major high point of his career and he is currently pondering his next project. A [[The Birds (film)|raven]] lands on his shoulder, before he turns to meet with his wife.\n\nThe final title cards say that Hitchcock directed six more films after ''Psycho'', none of which would eclipse its commercial success, and although he never won an [[Academy Award|Oscar]], the [[American Film Institute]] awarded him its Life Achievement Award in 1979: an award that he claimed he shared, as he had his life, with his wife, Alma.\n\n==Cast==\n<!--- Cast and order per tombstone closing credits, plus some historical, roles per closing credits scroll --->\n{{castlist|\n*[[Anthony Hopkins]] as [[Alfred Hitchcock]]\n*[[Helen Mirren]] as [[Alma Reville]]\n*[[Scarlett Johansson]] as [[Janet Leigh]]\n*[[Toni Collette]] as [[Peggy Robertson|Peggy]]\n*[[Danny Huston]] as [[Whitfield Cook]]\n*[[Jessica Biel]] as [[Vera Miles]]\n*[[Michael Stuhlbarg]] as [[Lew Wasserman]]\n*[[James D'Arcy]] as [[Anthony Perkins]]\n*[[Michael Wincott]] as [[Ed Gein]]\n*[[Kurtwood Smith]] as Geoffrey Shurlock\n*[[Richard Portnow]] as [[Barney Balaban]]\n*[[Ralph Macchio]] as [[Joseph Stefano]]\n*[[Wallace Langham]] as [[Saul Bass]]\n*Paul Schackman as [[Bernard Herrmann]]\n*Richard Chassler as [[Martin Balsam]]\n*Josh Yeo as [[John Gavin]]\n}}\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nIn 2005, it was reported that [[A&E (TV channel)|A&E]] would produce a television film or [[miniseries]] based on [[Stephen Rebello]]'s book ''[[Alfred Hitchcock and the Making of Psycho]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Martin|first=Denise|title=A&E looks into 'Live'|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117925863?refCatId=14|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=September 17, 2012|date=July 13, 2005}}</ref> Subsequently, the book was optioned as a major motion picture. In 2007, [[The Montecito Picture Company]], owned by [[Ivan Reitman]] and Tom Pollock, set up a [[first-look deal]] with [[Paramount Pictures]], the original distributor of ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]''. However, after four years of development at Paramount, production moved to [[Fox Searchlight Pictures]].<ref name=\"HelenMirren\">{{cite web|last=Kit|first=Borys|title=Helen Mirren Circling 'Alfred Hitchcock' as Project Moves From Paramount to Fox Searchlight (Exclusive)|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/helen-mirren-alfred-hitchcock-271024|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=September 17, 2012|date=December 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn November 20, 2011, [[Sacha Gervasi]] was announced as being in negotiations to direct the dramatic motion picture. Early the next month, Gervasi signed on as director with [[Anthony Hopkins]] and [[Helen Mirren]] attached to star as [[Alfred Hitchcock]] and [[Alma Reville]], respectively.<ref name=\"HelenMirren\" /> ''[[Black Swan (film)|Black Swan]]'' co-writer John J. McLaughlin wrote the first screenplay drafts; subsequently, Rebello wrote additional uncredited drafts that shifted the story's focus away from [[Ed Gein]] and instead toward the complex personal and professional relationship of Hitchcock and his wife, Reville, during the filming of ''Psycho''.\n\n===Casting===\nMuch of the film's casting was announced in March 2012. On March 1, 2012, [[Scarlett Johansson]] and [[James D'Arcy]] were announced to play the stars of ''Psycho'', [[Janet Leigh]] and [[Anthony Perkins]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Trumbore|first=Dave|title=Scarlett Johansson and James D\u2019Arcy Join ALFRED HITCHCOCK AND THE MAKING OF PSYCHO|url=http://collider.com/alfred-hitchcock-and-the-making-of-psycho-scarlett-johansson-james-darcy/149606/|publisher=Collider.com|accessdate=September 17, 2012|date=March 1, 2012}}</ref> Later that month [[Jessica Biel]] was cast as [[Vera Miles]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Donnelly|first=Matt|title=Jessica Biel nabs coveted 'Hitchcock' role as Vera Miles|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/gossip/2012/03/jessica-biel-joins-hitchock-movie-scarlett-johansson.html|publisher=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=September 17, 2012|date=March 21, 2012}}</ref> Following, additional cast members were announced that included [[Toni Collette]] as the director's trusted assistant, [[Danny Huston]] as screenwriter-playwright Whitfield Cook, [[Michael Stuhlbarg]] as powerful agent and studio boss [[Lew Wasserman]], [[Michael Wincott]] as [[serial killer]] [[Ed Gein]], [[Ralph Macchio]] as screenwriter [[Joseph Stefano]], [[Richard Portnow]] as [[Paramount Pictures]] boss [[Barney Balaban]], and [[Wallace Langham]] as graphic designer [[Saul Bass]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Gallagher|first=Brian|title=Toni Collette and Danny Huston Join Alfred Hitchcock and the Making of Psycho|url=http://www.movieweb.com/news/toni-collette-and-danny-huston-join-alfred-hitchcock-and-the-making-of-psycho|publisher=Movieweb|accessdate=September 17, 2012|date=March 21, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Original Karate Kid Ralph Macchio Joins Alfred Hitchock & The Making of Psycho|url=http://whatculture.com/film/original-karate-kid-ralph-macchio-joins-alfred-hitchock-the-making-of-psycho.php|accessdate=September 17, 2012|date=April 18, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203093412/http://whatculture.com/film/original-karate-kid-ralph-macchio-joins-alfred-hitchock-the-making-of-psycho.php|archivedate=February 3, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n[[Principal photography]] for the film began on April 13 in Los Angeles, with the film retitled as ''Hitchcock''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Savage|first=Sophia|title=Gervasi's 'Hitchcock' Shortens Title & Calls Itself A Love Story; Shoots April 13 in LA with Hopkins, Mirren & Johansson|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/thompsononhollywood/scarlett-johansson-lands-janet-leigh-role-in-alfred-hitchcock-and-the-making-of-psycho-trailers#|publisher=Indiewire|accessdate=September 17, 2012|date=April 12, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306132445/http://blogs.indiewire.com/thompsononhollywood/scarlett-johansson-lands-janet-leigh-role-in-alfred-hitchcock-and-the-making-of-psycho-trailers|archive-date=March 6, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> Filming was wrapped up on May 31 after the completion of a scene set during ''Psycho''{{'}}s New York City premiere on June 16, 1960.<ref>{{cite web|last=Horgan|first=Richard|title=UCLA Prof, Students Visit Sacha Gervasi\u2019s Hitchcock Set|url=http://www.mediabistro.com/fishbowlla/sacha-gervasi-hitchcock-psycho-anthony-hopkins-howard-suber-ucla-herve-villechaize_b63661|publisher=Mediabistro|accessdate=September 17, 2012|date=June 4, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120614135224/http://www.mediabistro.com/fishbowlla/sacha-gervasi-hitchcock-psycho-anthony-hopkins-howard-suber-ucla-herve-villechaize_b63661|archive-date=June 14, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\nOn September 12, 2012, it was announced that [[Danny Elfman]] would compose the film's score.<ref>{{cite web|last=Trumbore|first=Dave|title=Danny Elfman to Score Gus Van Sant\u2019s PROMISED LAND and Sacha Gervasi\u2019s HITCHCOCK, Both of Which May Debut Early to Qualify for 2012 Oscars|url=http://collider.com/danny-elfman-promised-land-hitchcock/195144/|publisher=Collider|accessdate=September 12, 2012}}</ref> Elfman had previously rerecorded [[Bernard Herrmann]]'s original score to ''Psycho'' in 1998 for [[Gus Van Sant]]'s [[Psycho (1998 film)|1998 shot-for-shot remake]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Browne|first=David|title=Psycho: Music From and Inspired by the Motion Picture|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,273973,00.html|publisher=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=September 20, 2012|date=January 8, 1999}}</ref>\n\nThe soundtrack album to the film was released by [[Sony Classical]] on December 14, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=Original Motion Picture Soundtrack Of \"HITCHCOCK\" With Music By Danny Elfman Available December 4, 2012|url=http://www.sacbee.com/2012/11/16/4991731/original-motion-picture-soundtrack.html|publisher=The Sacramento Bee|accessdate=November 20, 2012|date=November 16, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121120003004/http://www.sacbee.com/2012/11/16/4991731/original-motion-picture-soundtrack.html|archivedate=November 20, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n[[Searchlight Pictures|Fox Searchlight Pictures]] announced on September 20, 2012, via their Twitter page, that ''Hitchcock'' would open in [[limited release]] on November 23, 2012, in order for the film to contend during [[Academy Award|Oscar]] season.<ref name=\"HP\">{{cite web|last=Rosen|first=Christopher|title='Hitchcock' Release Date: Anthony Hopkins Drama Set For Nov. 23, 2012|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/09/20/hitchcock-release-date-nov-23_n_1900904.html|publisher=Huffington Post|accessdate=September 20, 2012|date=September 20, 2012}}</ref> The film had its world premiere as the opening film of [[AFI Fest]] 2012 on November 1 with a gala at [[Grauman's Chinese Theatre]] in Hollywood.<ref>{{cite web|last=Olsen|first=Mark|title='Hitchcock' to open AFI Film Festival|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/moviesnow/la-et-mn-hitchcock-to-open-afi-film-festival-20120927,0,6880291.story|publisher=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=October 1, 2012|date=September 27, 2012}}</ref> The first trailer for the film was released on October 10, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|last=Chitwood|first=Adam|title=First Trailer and New Poster for HITCHCOCK Starring Anthony Hopkins|url=http://collider.com/hitchcock-trailer-poster/196992/|publisher=Collider.com|accessdate=October 10, 2012|date=October 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\n''Hitchcock'' was released onto DVD and Blu-ray on March 12, 2013 by [[20th Century Fox Home Entertainment]]. The home media releases contain several making-of featurettes as well as commentary between director Sacha Gervasi and author Stephen Rebello, a deleted scene, and the film's theatrical trailer.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hitchcock Blu-ray (Updated)|url=http://www.blu-ray.com/news/?id=10155|publisher=Blu-ray.com|accessdate=May 31, 2013|date=January 8, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n''Hitchcock'' has earned an estimated $24.7 million worldwide.<ref name=\"the-numbers.com\">http://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Hitchcock#tab=more Retrieved October 23, 2017.</ref> During its opening on Thanksgiving weekend, the film debuted in 17 theaters and grossed an average of $16,924 per theater.<ref>{{cite web|last=Subers|first=Ray|title=Weekend Report: 'Twilight,' Bond Dominate Fruitful Thanksgiving|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=3574&p=.htm|publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=November 26, 2012|date=November 25, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\n''Hitchcock'' received mixed reviews from the critics. Review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]] gives a rating of 60%, based on 214 reviews, with an average rating of 6.2/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"Though it suffers from tonal inconsistency and a lack of truly insightful retrospection, ''Hitchcock'' is elevated by inspired performances from its two distinguished leads.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/hitchcock/|title=Hitchcock (2012)|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|accessdate=August 22, 2018}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a score of 55 out of 100, based on 40 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/hitchcock|title=Hitchcock Reviews|work=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=March 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\nSoon after the [[Film premiere|film's world premiere]] at the [[AFI Fest]] 2012, the first reviews of ''Hitchcock'' were published. Tom O'Neil of ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' wrote, \"When the film unspooled at AFI Fest on Thursday night, the audience burst into wild huzzahs at the end. This ''Hitchcock'' is so well made, so much fun and so suspenseful that it would make the original Hitchcock proud ... It's a serious contender for [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], [[Academy Award for Best Actor|Lead Actor]], [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Lead Actress]], [[Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Adapted Screenplay]], [[Academy Award for Best Makeup and Hairstyling|Makeup]], [[Academy Award for Best Original Score|Music Score]], and maybe [[Academy Award for Best Production Design|Art Direction]].\"<ref>{{cite web|last=O'Neil|first=Tom|title=Hitchcock Adds Suspense to the Oscars Race|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/tom-oneil/hitchcock-movie_b_2068598.html|publisher=The Huffington Post|accessdate=November 7, 2012|date=November 3, 2012}}</ref> John Patterson of ''[[The Guardian]]'' called the film \"clever and witty\"; \"the making of ''Psycho'' is depicted in detail without our seeing one frame of the completed movie\" and concluding \"it lives and breathes through Hopkins and Mirren.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Patterson|first=John|title=Hitchcock \u2013 first look review|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2012/nov/02/hitchcock-first-look-review|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=November 7, 2012|date=November 2, 2012}}</ref>\n\nUpon its theatrical release, Mary Pols of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' called the film \"a feel-good frolic, which is fine for anyone who prefers their Hitchcock history tidied up, absent the megalomania, the condescending cruelty and tendency to sexual harassment that caused his post-''Psycho'' blonde discovery [[Tippi Hedren]] to declare him 'a mean, mean man.'\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Pols|first=Mary|title=Hitchcock: To Psycho with Love|url=http://entertainment.time.com/2012/11/20/hitchcock-to-psycho-with-love/|publisher=Time Magazine|accessdate=November 20, 2012|date=November 20, 2012}}</ref> [[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' gave the film a positive review and felt that the film depended most on Helen Mirren's portrayal of Alma Reville, which he found to be \"warm and effective.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Ebert|first=Roger|title=Hitchcock|url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20121120/REVIEWS/121129996|publisher=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|accessdate=November 21, 2012|date=November 20, 2012}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Atlantic]]''{{'}}s [[Govindini Murty]] called the film \"smart and entertaining\" and also provided a cultural guide to the themes, personalities, and cinematic references in the film, from [[German Expressionism]] to the paintings of [[Edward Hopper]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Murty|first=Govindini|title=Catching the References in 'Hitchcock,' From 'The Birds' to the Blondes|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2012/11/catching-the-reference-in-hitchcock-from-the-birds-to-the-blondes/265606/|publisher=The Atlantic|accessdate=November 28, 2012|date=November 28, 2012}}</ref>\n\nMany critics compared the film to the [[HBO]] biopic ''[[The Girl (2012 TV film)|The Girl]]'', which was released a month earlier and detailed Hitchcock making ''[[The Birds (film)|The Birds]]'' and ''[[Marnie (film)|Marnie]]''. Justin Chang of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' wrote that \"the comparatively frothy ''Hitchcock'' offers a more sympathetic, even comedic assessment of the man behind the portly silhouette.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Chang|first=Justin|title=Variety Reviews \u2013 Hitchcock|url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117948672 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=November 20, 2012|date=November 2, 2012}}</ref> [[Todd McCarthy]] of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' also made note that the film \"brings a measure of authenticity entirely missing from ''The Girl''.\" When writing about the film as a whole, McCarthy said, \"''Hitchcock'' might be a work of fantasy and speculation as much as it is history and biography, but as an interpretation of a major talent's inner life and imagination, it's undeniably lively and provocative.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=McCarthy|first=Todd|title=Hitchcock Review|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/movie/hitchcock/review/385938|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=November 20, 2012|date=November 2, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{|class=wikitable\n!Award\n!Category\n!Recipients and nominees\n!Result\n|-\n|[[85th Academy Awards|Academy Awards]]\n|[[Academy Award for Best Makeup and Hairstyling|Best Makeup and Hairstyling]]\n|[[Howard Berger]], Peter Montagna and [[Martin Samuel (make-up artist)|Martin Samuel]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Alliance of Women Film Journalists]]\n|Actress Defying Age and Ageism\n|Helen Mirren\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[British Academy Film Awards]]\n|[[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Leading Role|Best Actress]]\n|Helen Mirren\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[BAFTA Award for Best Makeup and Hair|Best Makeup and Hair]]\n|\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Dallas-Fort Worth Film Critics Association]]\n|Best Actress\n|Helen Mirren\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Golden Globe Awards]]\n|[[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Drama|Best Motion Picture Actress \u2013 Drama]]\n|Helen Mirren\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Houston Film Critics Society]]\n|Best Score\n|\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[London Film Critics Circle]]\n|British Actress of the Year\n|Helen Mirren\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|Phoenix Film Critics Society\n|Best Actor\n|Anthony Hopkins\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|Best Original Score\n|Danny Elfman\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Saturn Award]]s\n| Best Independent Film\n|\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Saturn Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]]\n|Helen Mirren\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Saturn Award for Best Make-Up|Best Make-Up]]\n|Gregory Nicotero, Howard Berger, Peter Montagna and Julie Hewitt\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Screen Actors Guild Award]]s<ref name=\"SAG-2012\">{{cite news|last=Knegt|first=Peter|url=http://www.indiewire.com/article/silver-linings-lincoln-lead-sag-award-nominations|title=''Silver Linings'', ''Lincoln'', ''Les Mis'' Lead SAG Award Nominations|work=IndieWire|publisher=A SnagFilms Co|date=December 12, 2012|accessdate=December 12, 2012}}</ref>\n| [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Leading Role|Best Actress]]\n| Helen Mirren\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[St. Louis Gateway Film Critics Association]]\n|Best Actress\n|Helen Mirren\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|Best Scene\n|Anthony Hopkins in lobby conducting to music/audience\u2019s reaction during \u201cPsycho\u201d shower scene\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[Washington DC Area Film Critics Association]]\n|Best Actress\n|Helen Mirren\n|{{nom}}\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*''[[The Girl (2012 TV film)|The Girl]]'', a 2012 [[BBC]]/[[HBO]] biographical television film starring [[Toby Jones]] as Hitchcock about the making of ''[[The Birds (film)|The Birds]]'' and ''[[Marnie (film)|Marnie]]''.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2012/12/24/167539437/fact-checking-hitchcock-the-man-the-movie-and-the-myth|title=Fact Checking 'Hitchcock': The Man, The Movie and the Myth|author=NPR Staff|date=December 18, 2012|website=NPR|accessdate=December 30, 2012}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.hitchcockthemovie.com/}}\n*{{IMDb title|0975645}}\n*{{AllMovie title|415854}}\n*{{metacritic film|hitchcock}}\n*{{mojo title|hitchcock}}\n*{{Rotten Tomatoes|hitchcock}}\n\n{{Psycho|state=collapsed}}\n{{Alfred Hitchcock}}\n{{Alma Reville}}\n{{Sacha Gervasi}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hitchcock}}\n[[Category:2012 films]]\n[[Category:2010s comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American biographical films]]\n[[Category:American comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Ed Gein]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about film directors and producers]]\n[[Category:Films about filmmaking]]\n[[Category:Films about films]]\n[[Category:Films based on non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:Films based on biographies]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Danny Elfman]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Ivan Reitman]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1944]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1959]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1960]]\n[[Category:Films set in studio lots]]\n[[Category:Fox Searchlight Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Psycho (franchise) films]]\n[[Category:Works about Alfred Hitchcock]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2012 film by Sacha Gervasi}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Hitchcock\n| image          = Hitchcock film poster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Sacha Gervasi]]\n| producer       = [[Ivan Reitman]]<br>[[Tom Pollock]]<br>[[Joe Medjuck]]<br>Tom Thayer<br>Alan Barnette\n| screenplay     = John J. McLaughlin\n| based on       = {{based on|''[[Alfred Hitchcock and the Making of Psycho]]''|[[Stephen Rebello]]}}\n| starring       = [[Anthony Hopkins]]<br>[[Helen Mirren]]<br>[[Scarlett Johansson]]<br>[[Toni Collette]]<br>[[Danny Huston]]<br>[[Jessica Biel]]<br>[[James D'Arcy]]<br>[[Michael Wincott]]<!-- PER BILLING BLOCK -->\n| music          = [[Danny Elfman]]\n| cinematography = [[Jeff Cronenweth]]\n| editing        = [[Pamela Martin (film editor)|Pamela Martin]]\n| studio         = [[The Montecito Picture Company]]<br>Cold Spring Pictures<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/executive-suite-tom-pollock-ivan-165068 |title=Executive Suite: Tom Pollock and Ivan Reitman |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=2011-10-03 |accessdate=2014-01-25}}</ref> \n| distributor    = [[Searchlight Pictures|Fox Searchlight Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2012|11|01|[[AFI Fest]]|2012|11|23|United States}}\n| runtime        = 98 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 98:12--><ref>{{cite web|title=''HITCHCOCK'' (12A)|url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/AFF295678/|work=[[British Board of Film Classification]]|date=November 13, 2012|accessdate=2012-11-13}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $15 million<ref>https://www.screendaily.com/features/awards-countdown/hitchcock-psycho-path/5049543.article</ref>\n| gross          = $27 million<ref name=\"the-numbers.com\">http://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Hitchcock#tab=more Retrieved October 23, 2017.</ref> \n}}\n'''''Hitchcock''''' is a 2012 American [[Biographical film|biographical]] [[drama (film and television)|drama film]] directed by [[Sacha Gervasi]], based on [[Stephen Rebello]]'s non-fiction book ''[[Alfred Hitchcock and the Making of Psycho]]''. The film was released in selected cities on November 23, 2012,<ref name=\"HP\" /> with a worldwide release on December 14, 2012.\n\n''Hitchcock'' centers on the relationship between film director [[Alfred Hitchcock]] ([[Anthony Hopkins]]) and his wife [[Alma Reville]] ([[Helen Mirren]]) during the making of ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]'', a controversial [[horror film]] that became one of the most acclaimed and influential works in the filmmaker's career.\n\n==Plot ==\nIn 1959, Alfred Hitchcock opens his latest film, ''[[North by Northwest]]'', to both critical and commercial success, but is troubled by a reporter's insinuation that he should retire. Seeking to reclaim the artistic daring of his youth, Hitchcock turns down film proposals, including ''[[Casino Royale (novel)|Casino Royale]]'' and ''[[The Diary of Anne Frank (1959 film)|The Diary of Anne Frank]]'', in favor of a horror novel called ''[[Psycho (novel)|Psycho]]'' by [[Robert Bloch]],  based on the real-life crimes of murderer [[Ed Gein]]. Gein appears in sequences throughout the film, in which he seems to prompt Hitchcock's imagination regarding the ''Psycho'' story, or act as some function of Hitchcock's subconscious mind (for instance, drawing Hitchcock's attention to sand on his bathroom floor, the quantity of which reveals how much time his wife Alma has been spending at the beachhouse with Whitfield Cook).\n\nHitchcock's wife and artistic collaborator, Alma, is no more enthusiastic about the idea than his colleagues, especially since she is being lobbied by their writer friend, [[Whitfield Cook]], to look at his own screenplay. However, she warms to Hitchcock's proposal, suggesting the innovative plot turn of killing the female lead early in the film. The studio heads at [[Paramount Pictures|Paramount]] prove more difficult to persuade, forcing Hitchcock to finance the film personally and use his ''[[Alfred Hitchcock Presents]]'' television crew (over at competitor Revue/Universal) to shoot the film, his last with Paramount.\n\nHowever, the pressures of the production, such as dealing with Geoffrey Shurlock of the [[Motion Picture Production Code]], and Hitchcock's lecherous habits, such as when they confer with the female lead, [[Janet Leigh]], annoy Alma. She begins a personal writing collaboration with Whitfield Cook on his screenplay at his beach house without Hitchcock's knowledge. Hitchcock eventually discovers what she has been doing and suspects her of having an affair.  This concern affects Hitchcock's work on ''Psycho''. Hitchcock eventually confronts Alma and asks her if she is having an affair. Alma angrily denies it.\n\nAlma temporarily takes over production of the film when Hitchcock is bedridden after collapsing from overwork, but this sequence, which included a complicated [[Rear projection effect|process shot]] showing Detective Arbogast's demise, with Alma's specification of a 35mm lens, instead of the 50mm lens preferred by Hitchcock for this film, proved to be the least effective in the film.\n\nMeanwhile, Hitchcock expresses his disappointment to [[Vera Miles]] at how she didn't follow through on his plan to make her the next biggest star after [[Grace Kelly]], but Miles says she is happy with her family life.\n\nHitchcock's cut of ''Psycho'' is poorly received by the studio executives, while Alma discovers Whitfield having sex with a younger woman at his beach house. Hitchcock and Alma reconcile and set to work on improving the film. Their renewed collaboration yields results, culminating in Alma persuading Hitchcock to accept their composer's suggestion for adding [[Bernard Herrmann]]'s harsh strings score to the shower scene.\n\nAfter maneuvering Shurlock into leaving the film's content largely intact, Hitchcock learns the studio is only going to open the film in two theaters. Hitchcock arranges for special theater instructions to pique the public's interest such as forbidding admittance after the film begins. At the film's premiere, Hitchcock first views the audience from the projection booth, looking out through its small window at them. Hitchcock then waits in the lobby for the audience's reaction, conducting slashing motions to their reactions as they scream on cue. The film is rewarded with an enthusiastic reception.\n\nWith the film's screening so well received, Hitchcock publicly thanks his wife for helping make it possible and they affirm their love and partnership. At the conclusion at his home, Hitchcock addresses the audience noting ''Psycho'' proved a major high point of his career and he is currently pondering his next project. A [[The Birds (film)|raven]] lands on his shoulder, before he turns to meet with his wife.\n\nThe final title cards say that Hitchcock directed six more films after ''Psycho'', none of which would eclipse its commercial success, and although he never won an [[Academy Award|Oscar]], the [[American Film Institute]] awarded him its Life Achievement Award in 1979: an award that he claimed he shared, as he had his life, with his wife, Alma.\n\n==Cast==\n<!--- Cast and order per tombstone closing credits, plus some historical, roles per closing credits scroll --->\n{{castlist|\n*[[Anthony Hopkins]] as [[Alfred Hitchcock]]\n*[[Helen Mirren]] as [[Alma Reville]]\n*[[Scarlett Johansson]] as [[Janet Leigh]]\n*[[Toni Collette]] as [[Peggy Robertson|Peggy]]\n*[[Danny Huston]] as [[Whitfield Cook]]\n*[[Jessica Biel]] as [[Vera Miles]]\n*[[Michael Stuhlbarg]] as [[Lew Wasserman]]\n*[[James D'Arcy]] as [[Anthony Perkins]]\n*[[Michael Wincott]] as [[Ed Gein]]\n*[[Kurtwood Smith]] as Geoffrey Shurlock\n*[[Richard Portnow]] as [[Barney Balaban]]\n*[[Ralph Macchio]] as [[Joseph Stefano]]\n*[[Wallace Langham]] as [[Saul Bass]]\n*Paul Schackman as [[Bernard Herrmann]]\n*Richard Chassler as [[Martin Balsam]]\n*Josh Yeo as [[John Gavin]]\n}}\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nIn 2005, it was reported that [[A&E (TV channel)|A&E]] would produce a television film or [[miniseries]] based on [[Stephen Rebello]]'s book ''[[Alfred Hitchcock and the Making of Psycho]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Martin|first=Denise|title=A&E looks into 'Live'|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117925863?refCatId=14|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=September 17, 2012|date=July 13, 2005}}</ref> Subsequently, the book was optioned as a major motion picture. In 2007, [[The Montecito Picture Company]], owned by [[Ivan Reitman]] and Tom Pollock, set up a [[first-look deal]] with [[Paramount Pictures]], the original distributor of ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]''. However, after four years of development at Paramount, production moved to [[Fox Searchlight Pictures]].<ref name=\"HelenMirren\">{{cite web|last=Kit|first=Borys|title=Helen Mirren Circling 'Alfred Hitchcock' as Project Moves From Paramount to Fox Searchlight (Exclusive)|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/helen-mirren-alfred-hitchcock-271024|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=September 17, 2012|date=December 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn November 20, 2011, [[Sacha Gervasi]] was announced as being in negotiations to direct the dramatic motion picture. Early the next month, Gervasi signed on as director with [[Anthony Hopkins]] and [[Helen Mirren]] attached to star as [[Alfred Hitchcock]] and [[Alma Reville]], respectively.<ref name=\"HelenMirren\" /> ''[[Black Swan (film)|Black Swan]]'' co-writer John J. McLaughlin wrote the first screenplay drafts; subsequently, Rebello wrote additional uncredited drafts that shifted the story's focus away from [[Ed Gein]] and instead toward the complex personal and professional relationship of Hitchcock and his wife, Reville, during the filming of ''Psycho''.\n\n===Casting===\nMuch of the film's casting was announced in March 2012. On March 1, 2012, [[Scarlett Johansson]] and [[James D'Arcy]] were announced to play the stars of ''Psycho'', [[Janet Leigh]] and [[Anthony Perkins]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Trumbore|first=Dave|title=Scarlett Johansson and James D\u2019Arcy Join ALFRED HITCHCOCK AND THE MAKING OF PSYCHO|url=http://collider.com/alfred-hitchcock-and-the-making-of-psycho-scarlett-johansson-james-darcy/149606/|publisher=Collider.com|accessdate=September 17, 2012|date=March 1, 2012}}</ref> Later that month [[Jessica Biel]] was cast as [[Vera Miles]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Donnelly|first=Matt|title=Jessica Biel nabs coveted 'Hitchcock' role as Vera Miles|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/gossip/2012/03/jessica-biel-joins-hitchock-movie-scarlett-johansson.html|publisher=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=September 17, 2012|date=March 21, 2012}}</ref> Following, additional cast members were announced that included [[Toni Collette]] as the director's trusted assistant, [[Danny Huston]] as screenwriter-playwright Whitfield Cook, [[Michael Stuhlbarg]] as powerful agent and studio boss [[Lew Wasserman]], [[Michael Wincott]] as [[serial killer]] [[Ed Gein]], [[Ralph Macchio]] as screenwriter [[Joseph Stefano]], [[Richard Portnow]] as [[Paramount Pictures]] boss [[Barney Balaban]], and [[Wallace Langham]] as graphic designer [[Saul Bass]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Gallagher|first=Brian|title=Toni Collette and Danny Huston Join Alfred Hitchcock and the Making of Psycho|url=http://www.movieweb.com/news/toni-collette-and-danny-huston-join-alfred-hitchcock-and-the-making-of-psycho|publisher=Movieweb|accessdate=September 17, 2012|date=March 21, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Original Karate Kid Ralph Macchio Joins Alfred Hitchock & The Making of Psycho|url=http://whatculture.com/film/original-karate-kid-ralph-macchio-joins-alfred-hitchock-the-making-of-psycho.php|accessdate=September 17, 2012|date=April 18, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203093412/http://whatculture.com/film/original-karate-kid-ralph-macchio-joins-alfred-hitchock-the-making-of-psycho.php|archivedate=February 3, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n[[Principal photography]] for the film began on April 13 in Los Angeles, with the film retitled as ''Hitchcock''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Savage|first=Sophia|title=Gervasi's 'Hitchcock' Shortens Title & Calls Itself A Love Story; Shoots April 13 in LA with Hopkins, Mirren & Johansson|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/thompsononhollywood/scarlett-johansson-lands-janet-leigh-role-in-alfred-hitchcock-and-the-making-of-psycho-trailers#|publisher=Indiewire|accessdate=September 17, 2012|date=April 12, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306132445/http://blogs.indiewire.com/thompsononhollywood/scarlett-johansson-lands-janet-leigh-role-in-alfred-hitchcock-and-the-making-of-psycho-trailers|archive-date=March 6, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> Filming was wrapped up on May 31 after the completion of a scene set during ''Psycho''{{'}}s New York City premiere on June 16, 1960.<ref>{{cite web|last=Horgan|first=Richard|title=UCLA Prof, Students Visit Sacha Gervasi\u2019s Hitchcock Set|url=http://www.mediabistro.com/fishbowlla/sacha-gervasi-hitchcock-psycho-anthony-hopkins-howard-suber-ucla-herve-villechaize_b63661|publisher=Mediabistro|accessdate=September 17, 2012|date=June 4, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120614135224/http://www.mediabistro.com/fishbowlla/sacha-gervasi-hitchcock-psycho-anthony-hopkins-howard-suber-ucla-herve-villechaize_b63661|archive-date=June 14, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\nOn September 12, 2012, it was announced that [[Danny Elfman]] would compose the film's score.<ref>{{cite web|last=Trumbore|first=Dave|title=Danny Elfman to Score Gus Van Sant\u2019s PROMISED LAND and Sacha Gervasi\u2019s HITCHCOCK, Both of Which May Debut Early to Qualify for 2012 Oscars|url=http://collider.com/danny-elfman-promised-land-hitchcock/195144/|publisher=Collider|accessdate=September 12, 2012}}</ref> Elfman had previously rerecorded [[Bernard Herrmann]]'s original score to ''Psycho'' in 1998 for [[Gus Van Sant]]'s [[Psycho (1998 film)|1998 shot-for-shot remake]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Browne|first=David|title=Psycho: Music From and Inspired by the Motion Picture|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,273973,00.html|publisher=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=September 20, 2012|date=January 8, 1999}}</ref>\n\nThe soundtrack album to the film was released by [[Sony Classical]] on December 14, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=Original Motion Picture Soundtrack Of \"HITCHCOCK\" With Music By Danny Elfman Available December 4, 2012|url=http://www.sacbee.com/2012/11/16/4991731/original-motion-picture-soundtrack.html|publisher=The Sacramento Bee|accessdate=November 20, 2012|date=November 16, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121120003004/http://www.sacbee.com/2012/11/16/4991731/original-motion-picture-soundtrack.html|archivedate=November 20, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n[[Searchlight Pictures|Fox Searchlight Pictures]] announced on September 20, 2012, via their Twitter page, that ''Hitchcock'' would open in [[limited release]] on November 23, 2012, in order for the film to contend during [[Academy Award|Oscar]] season.<ref name=\"HP\">{{cite web|last=Rosen|first=Christopher|title='Hitchcock' Release Date: Anthony Hopkins Drama Set For Nov. 23, 2012|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/09/20/hitchcock-release-date-nov-23_n_1900904.html|publisher=Huffington Post|accessdate=September 20, 2012|date=September 20, 2012}}</ref> The film had its world premiere as the opening film of [[AFI Fest]] 2012 on November 1 with a gala at [[Grauman's Chinese Theatre]] in Hollywood.<ref>{{cite web|last=Olsen|first=Mark|title='Hitchcock' to open AFI Film Festival|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/moviesnow/la-et-mn-hitchcock-to-open-afi-film-festival-20120927,0,6880291.story|publisher=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=October 1, 2012|date=September 27, 2012}}</ref> The first trailer for the film was released on October 10, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|last=Chitwood|first=Adam|title=First Trailer and New Poster for HITCHCOCK Starring Anthony Hopkins|url=http://collider.com/hitchcock-trailer-poster/196992/|publisher=Collider.com|accessdate=October 10, 2012|date=October 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\n''Hitchcock'' was released onto DVD and Blu-ray on March 12, 2013 by [[20th Century Fox Home Entertainment]]. The home media releases contain several making-of featurettes as well as commentary between director Sacha Gervasi and author Stephen Rebello, a deleted scene, and the film's theatrical trailer.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hitchcock Blu-ray (Updated)|url=http://www.blu-ray.com/news/?id=10155|publisher=Blu-ray.com|accessdate=May 31, 2013|date=January 8, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n''Hitchcock'' has earned an estimated $24.7 million worldwide.<ref name=\"the-numbers.com\">http://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Hitchcock#tab=more Retrieved October 23, 2017.</ref> During its opening on Thanksgiving weekend, the film debuted in 17 theaters and grossed an average of $16,924 per theater.<ref>{{cite web|last=Subers|first=Ray|title=Weekend Report: 'Twilight,' Bond Dominate Fruitful Thanksgiving|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=3574&p=.htm|publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=November 26, 2012|date=November 25, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\n''Hitchcock'' received mixed reviews from the critics. Review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]] gives a rating of 60%, based on 214 reviews, with an average rating of 6.2/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"Though it suffers from tonal inconsistency and a lack of truly insightful retrospection, ''Hitchcock'' is elevated by inspired performances from its two distinguished leads.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/hitchcock/|title=Hitchcock (2012)|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|accessdate=August 22, 2018}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a score of 55 out of 100, based on 40 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/hitchcock|title=Hitchcock Reviews|work=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=March 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\nSoon after the [[Film premiere|film's world premiere]] at the [[AFI Fest]] 2012, the first reviews of ''Hitchcock'' were published. Tom O'Neil of ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' wrote, \"When the film unspooled at AFI Fest on Thursday night, the audience burst into wild huzzahs at the end. This ''Hitchcock'' is so well made, so much fun and so suspenseful that it would make the original Hitchcock proud ... It's a serious contender for [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], [[Academy Award for Best Actor|Lead Actor]], [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Lead Actress]], [[Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Adapted Screenplay]], [[Academy Award for Best Makeup and Hairstyling|Makeup]], [[Academy Award for Best Original Score|Music Score]], and maybe [[Academy Award for Best Production Design|Art Direction]].\"<ref>{{cite web|last=O'Neil|first=Tom|title=Hitchcock Adds Suspense to the Oscars Race|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/tom-oneil/hitchcock-movie_b_2068598.html|publisher=The Huffington Post|accessdate=November 7, 2012|date=November 3, 2012}}</ref> John Patterson of ''[[The Guardian]]'' called the film \"clever and witty\"; \"the making of ''Psycho'' is depicted in detail without our seeing one frame of the completed movie\" and concluding \"it lives and breathes through Hopkins and Mirren.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Patterson|first=John|title=Hitchcock \u2013 first look review|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2012/nov/02/hitchcock-first-look-review|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=November 7, 2012|date=November 2, 2012}}</ref>\n\nUpon its theatrical release, Mary Pols of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' called the film \"a feel-good frolic, which is fine for anyone who prefers their Hitchcock history tidied up, absent the megalomania, the condescending cruelty and tendency to sexual harassment that caused his post-''Psycho'' blonde discovery [[Tippi Hedren]] to declare him 'a mean, mean man.'\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Pols|first=Mary|title=Hitchcock: To Psycho with Love|url=http://entertainment.time.com/2012/11/20/hitchcock-to-psycho-with-love/|publisher=Time Magazine|accessdate=November 20, 2012|date=November 20, 2012}}</ref> [[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' gave the film a positive review and felt that the film depended most on Helen Mirren's portrayal of Alma Reville, which he found to be \"warm and effective.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Ebert|first=Roger|title=Hitchcock|url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20121120/REVIEWS/121129996|publisher=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|accessdate=November 21, 2012|date=November 20, 2012}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Atlantic]]''{{'}}s [[Govindini Murty]] called the film \"smart and entertaining\" and also provided a cultural guide to the themes, personalities, and cinematic references in the film, from [[German Expressionism]] to the paintings of [[Edward Hopper]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Murty|first=Govindini|title=Catching the References in 'Hitchcock,' From 'The Birds' to the Blondes|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2012/11/catching-the-reference-in-hitchcock-from-the-birds-to-the-blondes/265606/|publisher=The Atlantic|accessdate=November 28, 2012|date=November 28, 2012}}</ref>\n\nMany critics compared the film to the [[HBO]] biopic ''[[The Girl (2012 TV film)|The Girl]]'', which was released a month earlier and detailed Hitchcock making ''[[The Birds (film)|The Birds]]'' and ''[[Marnie (film)|Marnie]]''. Justin Chang of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' wrote that \"the comparatively frothy ''Hitchcock'' offers a more sympathetic, even comedic assessment of the man behind the portly silhouette.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Chang|first=Justin|title=Variety Reviews \u2013 Hitchcock|url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117948672 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=November 20, 2012|date=November 2, 2012}}</ref> [[Todd McCarthy]] of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' also made note that the film \"brings a measure of authenticity entirely missing from ''The Girl''.\" When writing about the film as a whole, McCarthy said, \"''Hitchcock'' might be a work of fantasy and speculation as much as it is history and biography, but as an interpretation of a major talent's inner life and imagination, it's undeniably lively and provocative.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=McCarthy|first=Todd|title=Hitchcock Review|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/movie/hitchcock/review/385938|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=November 20, 2012|date=November 2, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{|class=wikitable\n!Award\n!Category\n!Recipients and nominees\n!Result\n|-\n|[[Academy Awards]] <small>([[85th Academy Awards|85th]])\n|[[Academy Award for Best Makeup and Hairstyling|Best Makeup and Hairstyling]]\n|[[Howard Berger]], Peter Montagna and [[Martin Samuel (make-up artist)|Martin Samuel]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Alliance of Women Film Journalists]]\n|Actress Defying Age and Ageism\n|Helen Mirren\n|{{