sion film starring [[Toby Jones]] as Hitchcock about the making of ''[[The Birds (film)|The Birds]]'' and ''[[Marnie (film)|Marnie]]''.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2012/12/24/167539437/fact-checking-hitchcock-the-man-the-movie-and-the-myth|title=Fact Checking 'Hitchcock': The Man, The Movie and the Myth|author=NPR Staff|date=December 18, 2012|website=NPR|accessdate=December 30, 2012}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.hitchcockthemovie.com/}}\n*{{IMDb title|0975645}}\n*{{AllMovie title|415854}}\n*{{metacritic film|hitchcock}}\n*{{mojo title|hitchcock}}\n*{{Rotten Tomatoes|hitchcock}}\n\n{{Psycho|state=collapsed}}\n{{Alfred Hitchcock}}\n{{Alma Reville}}\n{{Sacha Gervasi}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hitchcock}}\n[[Category:2012 films]]\n[[Category:2010s comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American biographical films]]\n[[Category:American comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Ed Gein]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about film directors and producers]]\n[[Category:Films about filmmaking]]\n[[Category:Films about films]]\n[[Category:Films based on non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:Films based on biographies]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Danny Elfman]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Ivan Reitman]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1944]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1959]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1960]]\n[[Category:Films set in studio lots]]\n[[Category:Fox Searchlight Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Psycho (franchise) films]]\n[[Category:Works about Alfred Hitchcock]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAccolades", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hitchcock_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Mark Wood (explorer)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2017}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Mark Wood\n| image       = Mark Wood south pole solo.jpg\n| caption     = Mark Wood south pole solo.\n| birth_name = Mark Wood\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age |1966|3|1|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = Coventry, Warwickshire, England\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| education   = Stivichall Junior School<ref>{{cite web |title=Stivichall Primary School |url=https://www.stivichallprimary.org/ |website=Stivichall Primary School |publisher=Stivichall Primary School |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>, Coventry & Finham Park School<ref>{{cite web |title=Finham Park School |url=http://finhampark.com/ |website=Finham Park School |publisher=Finham Park School |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>, Coventry, \n| nationality = British\n| occupation  = [[British Army]] Firefighter in the Royal Berkshire, Fire and Rescue Service; explorer and expedition leader\n| awards      = [[Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal]], [[United Nations Medal]]\n| module      = {{Infobox military person|embed=yes\n| allegiance  = {{flag| United Kingdom}}\n| branch      = {{army| United Kingdom}}\n| serviceyears = \n| rank         = [[Fusilier#United Kingdom|Fusilier]]\n| servicenumber = \n| unit          = [[Royal Regiment of Fusiliers]]\n|website          = {{URL|www.markwoodexplorer.com}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Mark Wood''' [[Fellow of the Royal Geographical Society|FRGS]] (born 1966), is a [[British people|British]] adventurer and [[explorer]]. He served in the [[British Army]] in the Second Battalion, The Royal Regiment of Fusiliers, and as a firefighter in the Royal Berkshire [[Fire services in the United Kingdom| Fire and Rescue Service]]. He has trained and led teams for major polar and mountain expeditions in regions as far flung as the [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arctic_Circle| Arctic Circle], the Himalayas, [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antarctica| Antarctica], [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alaska| Alaska], and the Canadian and Norwegian High Arctic.\n\n==Early Life and Education==\nMark was born in Coventry and attended two local schools: Stivichall Junior School<ref>{{cite web |title=Stivichall Primary School |url=https://www.stivichallprimary.org/ |website=Stivichall Primary School |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> and Coventry Finham Park Comprehensive School.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coventry Finham Park School |url=http://finhampark.com/ |website=Coventry Finham Park School |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> Both schools are in [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coventry  Coventry], [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Warwickshire  Warwickshire], England.\n\n==Military==\nMark served in the [[British Army]] in the Second Battalion, The Royal Regiment of Fusiliers.\n\n==Firefighter==\n\n== Expedition Leader ==\n\nHe commenced his career as an expedition and explorer in 2003. Four years later he established a polar expedition company called Snowball Expeditions.<ref>{{cite web |title=Snowball Expeditions |url=https://www.facebook.com/snowballexpeditions |website=Snowball Expeditions |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>. Mark has on average undertaken an expedition every year. Each of his expeditions has a specific goal. \n\nIn 2011/2012 he attempted to become the first person in history to ski solo to both the [[South Pole|South]] and [[North Pole|North]] Poles. The aim of this expedition was to raise awareness of [[climate change]]. He left from the West coast of [[Antarctica]] ([[Hercules Inlet]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-coventry-warwickshire-15353195 |work=BBC News |title=Coventry man's solo polar expedition for climate change |publisher=BBC |date=19 October 2011 |accessdate=9 July 2012}}</ref> After reaching the South Pole in January 2012,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-coventry-warwickshire-17694043 |work=BBC News |title=Polar explorer Mark Wood reaches South Pole |publisher=BBC |date=10 January 2012 |accessdate=9 July 2012}}</ref> he continued his journey across 2 degrees of the [[Arctic Ocean]]. He crossed the [[North Pole]] and continuing to the Russian Ice Station. The expedition was cut short due to the fee required by the Canadian airline company which collects explorers who undertake on the Arctic Ocean.\n\nWood's attempt was continued to the North [[Geographical pole|Geographic pole]] to extend the school's programme{{Snd}} . Wood completed the 6-month \"North South Solo Expedition\" in April 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-coventry-warwickshire-17694043 |work=[[BBC News]] |title=Coventry explorer Mark Wood reaches North Pole |date=12 April 2012 |accessdate=9 July 2012 }}</ref>\n\nDuring his expeditions, Wood used the [[ipadio]] service via [[satellite phone]] to transmit video and make phone calls.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.ipadio.com/02/ipadio-in-action-at-the-south-pole |work=ipadio blog |date=2012-02-03 |title=ipadio in action&nbsp;... at the South Pole! |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130220094535/http://blog.ipadio.com/02/ipadio-in-action-at-the-south-pole |archivedate=20 February 2013 }}</ref>\n\n== Expeditions ==\n<!-- Is all of this notable? -->\n* 2019{{Snd}} [[Mount Everest]] ascent expedition - 8848 Expedition<ref>{{cite web |title=8848 - THE MOST EXTREME CLASSROOM ON THE PLANE |url=http://expedition8848.com/ |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n* 2018{{Snd}} Solo 200 filming in [[Kenya]]\n* 2018{{Snd}} Solo 100 filming in [[Alaska]]\n* 2017{{Snd}} Guided 30 military wives to [[Mount Everest]] base camp\n* 2016{{Snd}} Geographic North Pole expedition\n* 2015{{Snd}} North pole pre-training [[Norway]]\n* 2015{{Snd}} Unaided, unsupported crossing of [[Iceland]]\n* 2015{{Snd}} Education programme in the [[Himalayas]] for Skype in the Classroom<ref>{{cite web |title=Skype in the Classroom |url=https://educationblog.microsoft.com/en-us/tag/skype-in-the-classroom/ |website=Skype in the Classroom |publisher=Microsoft |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n* 2015{{Snd}} cycled across [[Oman]]\n* 2014{{Snd}} IGGY{{Snd}} Cycle New Zealand<ref>{{cite web |title=Cycling New Zealand Schools Education Programme |url=https://schools.cyclingnewzealand.nz/ |website=NZ Schools Cycling Association (NZSCA) |publisher=NZ Schools Cycling Association (NZSCA) |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> educational schools programme\n* 2013{{Snd}} [[Skype]] [[Mount Everest]] Ascent expedition called \"My Life In a Freezer\" reached over 40 countries around the globe\n* 2011/2012{{Snd}} solo expedition to the North and South Geographic poles\n* 2011{{Snd}} North South Solo training expedition{{Snd}} High Arctic [[Svalbard]]\n* 2010{{Snd}} Island Peak expedition{{Snd}} 6184&nbsp;m{{Snd}} [[Himalayas]]\n* 2010{{Snd}} Global Schools Project to the Himalayas{{Snd}} [[Warwick University]]\n* 2010{{Snd}} Himalayan expedition for the Global Schools project<ref>{{cite web |title=Global Schools Project |url=http://www.globalschools.education/Project |publisher=Global Schools Network |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n* 2010{{Snd}} A solo 30-day training expedition in [[Svalbard]]\n* 2009{{Snd}} Led 3 expeditions involving over 60 people to Everest BC{{Snd}} Snowball Exp, schools project\n* 2009{{Snd}} Led a British first expedition in the [[Arctic]]{{Snd}} highlighting the [[Inuit]] communities affected by climate change\n* 2009{{Snd}} Alaskan [[dog sledding]] expedition{{Snd}} filming for an educational films programme\n* 2008{{Snd}} Led a team through the [[Himalayas]] to [[Everest base camps|base camp Everest]] as part of an educational schools programme\n* 2008{{Snd}} Led an expedition linking the two highest [[Inuit]] settlements in the [[Canadian high Arctic]]\n* 2008{{Snd}} Filming for a documentary on how global warming is affecting the [[Inuit]] people\n* 2008{{Snd}} Led a dog sledging expedition in [[North America]]\n* 2007{{Snd}} Polar guide and provided operational support for [[BBC]] [[Top Gear (2002 series)|Top Gear]] programme, ''Race to the Pole''\n* 2007{{Snd}} Arctic expedition technical support for the Magnetic North Pole Race (1996 pole position)\n* 2006{{Snd}} Cycled across the [[United States]]{{Snd}} 3500 miles from [[Seattle]] to [[New York City|New York]]\n* 2006{{Snd}} Led an 8-person team on a successful Geomagnetic North Pole expedition\n* 2005/2006{{Snd}} Instructor on an Arctic training expedition{{Snd}} Northern [[Canada]]\n* 2005{{Snd}} Instructor on an Arctic training programme {{Snd}} [[Norway]]\n* 2004{{Snd}} Geomagnetic North Pole expedition\n* 2003{{Snd}} 70-day training expedition and research for [[Cancer Research UK]] (CRUK){{Snd}} Canadian High Arctic\n\n==Awards and Recognition==\n\n==Affiliations and Associations==\n* [[Chairperson|Chair]] of the Great Britain and Ireland Chapter, [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Explorers_Club  The Explorers Club]<ref>{{cite web |title=The Explorers Club: International Chapters |url=https://explorers.org/about/international_chapters |website=The Explorers Club |publisher=The Explorers Club |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n* Member of the [[The Explorers Club]], Norwegian Chapter<ref>{{cite web |title=Norwiegan Chapter, Explorers Club |url=https://www.facebook.com/explorersclubnorway |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n* [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Royal_Geographical_Society#Fellowship  Royal Geographical Society Fellowship] of the [[Royal Geographical Society]], [[London]], England\n* [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Explorer_(disambiguation)  Explorer] for IGGY<ref>{{cite web |last1=IGGY is an international network of the brightest and most creative young people aged 13-18. |title=Smart Connections: Mark Wood |url=https://www.iggy.net/ |publisher=Warwick University |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n* Polar Explorer for [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_Warwick  Warwick University]<ref>{{cite web |title=Warwick University - Polar Explorer |url=https://warwick.ac.uk/about/warwick50/content/connected/ |website=Warwick University |publisher=Warwick University |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n* Ambassador of [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Prince's_Trust  The Prince's Trust]\n\n==References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{URL|www.markwoodexplorer.com|Mark Wood{{Snd}} Explorer}}\n* {{URL|www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-coventry-warwickshire-15353195 |Coventry man's solo polar expedition for climate change}}\n* {{URL|www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-coventry-warwickshire-17694043 |Coventry explorer Mark Wood reaches North Pole}}\n\n{{Polar exploration|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wood, Mark}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Coventry]]\n[[Category:Explorers of the Arctic]]\n[[Category:21st-century explorers]]\n[[Category:British polar explorers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2017}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Mark Wood\n| image       = Mark Wood south pole solo.jpg\n| caption     = Mark Wood south pole solo.\n| birth_name = Mark Wood\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age |1966|3|1|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = Coventry, Warwickshire, England\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| education   = Stivichall Junior School<ref>{{cite web |title=Stivichall Primary School |url=https://www.stivichallprimary.org/ |website=Stivichall Primary School |publisher=Stivichall Primary School |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>, Coventry & Finham Park School<ref>{{cite web |title=Finham Park School |url=http://finhampark.com/ |website=Finham Park School |publisher=Finham Park School |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>, Coventry, \n| nationality = British\n| occupation  = [[British Army]] Firefighter in the Royal Berkshire, Fire and Rescue Service; explorer and expedition leader\n| awards      = [[Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal]], [[United Nations Medal]]\n| module      = {{Infobox military person|embed=yes\n| allegiance  = {{flag| United Kingdom}}\n| branch      = {{army| United Kingdom}}\n| serviceyears = \n| rank         = [[Fusilier#United Kingdom|Fusilier]]\n| servicenumber = \n| unit          = [[Royal Regiment of Fusiliers]]\n|website          = {{URL|www.markwoodexplorer.com}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Mark Wood''' [[Fellow of the Royal Geographical Society|FRGS]] (born 1966), is a [[British people|British]] adventurer and [[explorer]]. He served in the [[British Army]] in the Second Battalion, The Royal Regiment of Fusiliers, and as a firefighter in the Royal Berkshire [[Fire services in the United Kingdom| Fire and Rescue Service]]. He has trained and led teams for major polar and mountain expeditions in regions as far flung as the [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arctic_Circle| Arctic Circle], the Himalayas, [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antarctica| Antarctica], [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alaska| Alaska], and the Canadian and Norwegian High Arctic.\n\n==Early Life and Education==\nMark was born in Coventry and attended two local schools: Stivichall Junior School<ref>{{cite web |title=Stivichall Primary School |url=https://www.stivichallprimary.org/ |website=Stivichall Primary School |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> and Coventry Finham Park Comprehensive School.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coventry Finham Park School |url=http://finhampark.com/ |website=Coventry Finham Park School |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> Both schools are in [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coventry  Coventry], [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Warwickshire  Warwickshire], England.\n\n==Military==\nMark served in the [[British Army]] in the Second Battalion, The Royal Regiment of Fusiliers.\n\n==Firefighter==\n\n== Expedition Leader ==\n\nHe commenced his career as an expedition and explorer in 2003. Four years later he established a polar expedition company called Snowball Expeditions.<ref>{{cite web |title=Snowball Expeditions |url=https://www.facebook.com/snowballexpeditions |website=Snowball Expeditions |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>. Mark has on average undertaken an expedition every year. Each of his expeditions has a specific goal. \n\nIn 2011/2012 he attempted to become the first person in history to ski solo to both the [[South Pole|South]] and [[North Pole|North]] Poles. The aim of this expedition was to raise awareness of [[climate change]]. He left from the West coast of [[Antarctica]] ([[Hercules Inlet]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-coventry-warwickshire-15353195 |work=BBC News |title=Coventry man's solo polar expedition for climate change |publisher=BBC |date=19 October 2011 |accessdate=9 July 2012}}</ref> After reaching the South Pole in January 2012,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-coventry-warwickshire-17694043 |work=BBC News |title=Polar explorer Mark Wood reaches South Pole |publisher=BBC |date=10 January 2012 |accessdate=9 July 2012}}</ref> he continued his journey across 2 degrees of the [[Arctic Ocean]]. He crossed the [[North Pole]] and continuing to the Russian Ice Station. The expedition was cut short due to the fee required by the Canadian airline company which collects explorers who undertake on the Arctic Ocean.\n\nWood's attempt was continued to the North [[Geographical pole|Geographic pole]] to extend the school's programme{{Snd}} . Wood completed the 6-month \"North South Solo Expedition\" in April 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-coventry-warwickshire-17694043 |work=[[BBC News]] |title=Coventry explorer Mark Wood reaches North Pole |date=12 April 2012 |accessdate=9 July 2012 }}</ref>\n\nDuring his expeditions, Wood used the [[ipadio]] service via [[satellite phone]] to transmit video and make phone calls.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.ipadio.com/02/ipadio-in-action-at-the-south-pole |work=ipadio blog |date=2012-02-03 |title=ipadio in action&nbsp;... at the South Pole! |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130220094535/http://blog.ipadio.com/02/ipadio-in-action-at-the-south-pole |archivedate=20 February 2013 }}</ref>\n\n== Expeditions ==\n<!-- Is all of this notable? -->\n* 2019{{Snd}} [[Mount Everest]] ascent expedition - 8848 Expedition<ref>{{cite web |title=8848 - THE MOST EXTREME CLASSROOM ON THE PLANE |url=http://expedition8848.com/ |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n* 2018{{Snd}} Solo 200 filming in [[Kenya]]\n* 2018{{Snd}} Solo 100 filming in [[Alaska]]\n* 2017{{Snd}} Guided 30 military wives to [[Mount Everest]] base camp\n* 2016{{Snd}} Geographic North Pole expedition\n* 2015{{Snd}} North pole pre-training [[Norway]]\n* 2015{{Snd}} Unaided, unsupported crossing of [[Iceland]]\n* 2015{{Snd}} Education programme in the [[Himalayas]] for Skype in the Classroom<ref>{{cite web |title=Skype in the Classroom |url=https://educationblog.microsoft.com/en-us/tag/skype-in-the-classroom/ |website=Skype in the Classroom |publisher=Microsoft |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n* 2015{{Snd}} cycled across [[Oman]]\n* 2014{{Snd}} IGGY{{Snd}} Cycle New Zealand<ref>{{cite web |title=Cycling New Zealand Schools Education Programme |url=https://schools.cyclingnewzealand.nz/ |website=NZ Schools Cycling Association (NZSCA) |publisher=NZ Schools Cycling Association (NZSCA) |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> educational schools programme\n* 2013{{Snd}} [[Skype]] [[Mount Everest]] Ascent expedition called \"My Life In a Freezer\" reached over 40 countries around the globe\n* 2011/2012{{Snd}} solo expedition to the North and South Geographic poles\n* 2011{{Snd}} North South Solo training expedition{{Snd}} High Arctic [[Svalbard]]\n* 2010{{Snd}} Island Peak expedition{{Snd}} 6184&nbsp;m{{Snd}} [[Himalayas]]\n* 2010{{Snd}} Global Schools Project to the Himalayas{{Snd}} [[Warwick University]]\n* 2010{{Snd}} Himalayan expedition for the Global Schools project<ref>{{cite web |title=Global Schools Project |url=http://www.globalschools.education/Project |publisher=Global Schools Network |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n* 2010{{Snd}} A solo 30-day training expedition in [[Svalbard]]\n* 2009{{Snd}} Led 3 expeditions involving over 60 people to Everest BC{{Snd}} Snowball Exp, schools project\n* 2009{{Snd}} Led a British first expedition in the [[Arctic]]{{Snd}} highlighting the [[Inuit]] communities affected by climate change\n* 2009{{Snd}} Alaskan [[dog sledding]] expedition{{Snd}} filming for an educational films programme\n* 2008{{Snd}} Led a team through the [[Himalayas]] to [[Everest base camps|base camp Everest]] as part of an educational schools programme\n* 2008{{Snd}} Led an expedition linking the two highest [[Inuit]] settlements in the [[Canadian high Arctic]]\n* 2008{{Snd}} Filming for a documentary on how global warming is affecting the [[Inuit]] people\n* 2008{{Snd}} Led a dog sledging expedition in [[North America]]\n* 2007{{Snd}} Polar guide and provided operational support for [[BBC]] [[Top Gear (2002 series)|Top Gear]] programme, ''Race to the Pole''\n* 2007{{Snd}} Arctic expedition technical support for the Magnetic North Pole Race (1996 pole position)\n* 2006{{Snd}} Cycled across the [[United States]]{{Snd}} 3500 miles from [[Seattle]] to [[New York City|New York]]\n* 2006{{Snd}} Led an 8-person team on a successful Geomagnetic North Pole expedition\n* 2005/2006{{Snd}} Instructor on an Arctic training expedition{{Snd}} Northern [[Canada]]\n* 2005{{Snd}} Instructor on an Arctic training programme {{Snd}} [[Norway]]\n* 2004{{Snd}} Geomagnetic North Pole expedition\n* 2003{{Snd}} 70-day training expedition and research for [[Cancer Research UK]] (CRUK){{Snd}} Canadian High Arctic\n\n==Awards and Recognition==\n\n==Affiliations and Associations==\n* [[Chairperson|Chair]] of the Great Britain and Ireland Chapter, [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Explorers_Club  The Explorers Club]<ref>{{cite web |title=The Explorers Club: International Chapters |url=https://explorers.org/about/international_chapters |website=The Explorers Club |publisher=The Explorers Club |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n* Member of the [[The Explorers Club]], Norwegian Chapter<ref>{{cite web |title=Norwiegan Chapter, Explorers Club |url=https://www.facebook.com/explorersclubnorway |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n* [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Royal_Geographical_Society#Fellowship  Royal Geographical Society Fellowship] of the [[Royal Geographical Society]], [[London]], England\n* [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Explorer_(disambiguation)  Explorer] for IGGY<ref>{{cite web |last1=IGGY is an international network of the brightest and most creative young people aged 13-18. |title=Smart Connections: Mark Wood |url=https://www.iggy.net/ |publisher=Warwick University |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n* Polar Explorer for [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_Warwick  Warwick University]<ref>{{cite web |title=Warwick University - Polar Explorer |url=https://warwick.ac.uk/about/warwick50/content/connected/ |website=Warwick University |publisher=Warwick University |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n* Ambassador of [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Prince's_Trust  The Prince's Trust]\n\n==References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{URL|www.markwoodexplorer.com|Mark Wood{{Snd}} Explorer}}\n* {{URL|www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-coventry-warwickshire-15353195 |Coventry man's solo polar expedition for climate change}}\n\n{{Polar exploration|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wood, Mark}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Coventry]]\n[[Category:Explorers of the Arctic]]\n[[Category:21st-century explorers]]\n[[Category:British polar explorers]]\n", "name_user": "35winds", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:adding external link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mark_Wood_(explorer)"}
{"title_page": "The Dave Ramsey Show (radio program)", "text_new": "{{for|the TV program|The Dave Ramsey Show (TV program)}}\n{{Infobox Radio Show\n| show_name          = The Dave Ramsey Show\n| image              = \n| imagesize          = \n| caption            =\n| format             = Financial talk\n| runtime            = 3 hours per episode\n| creator            = [[Dave Ramsey]]\n| writer             = \n| executive_producer = Blake Thompson\n| starring           = [[Dave Ramsey]]\n| opentheme          = \"[[Baker Street (song)|Baker Street]]\" by [[Gerry Rafferty]]\n| endtheme           = \"[[Money (Pink Floyd song)|Money]]\" by [[Pink Floyd]]\n| country            = {{flagicon|United States}} [[United States]]\n| first_aired        = 1992\n| last_aired         = present\n| num_episodes       = \n| website            = http://www.daveramsey.com/radio\n| home_station       = 1510 [[WLAC]]\n| podcast\t     = \n}}\n\n'''The Dave Ramsey Show''' is a three-hour, [[Radio syndication|self-syndicated]] radio program and podcast, hosted by the [[Dave Ramsey|eponymous finance author and speaker]], that airs Monday through Friday from 2-5 PM [[Eastern Time Zone|ET]]. It is primarily broadcast from [[Brentwood, Tennessee]], though often during the summer it is broadcast via remote from Ramsey's lake house.<ref name=\"Axia Interview: Blake Thompson\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.axiaaudio.com/interviews/features/ramsey.htm|title=Axia Interview with Blake Thompson, producer of The Dave Ramsey Show|accessdate=2006-12-03|publisher=www.axiaaudio.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070313071456/http://www.axiaaudio.com/interviews/features/ramsey.htm|archivedate=2007-03-13}}</ref> {{As of|2008}}, it is one of the top ten [[List of most-listened-to radio programs|most-listened-to radio shows]].<ref name=talkers2008>{{cite news |url=http://www.talkers.com/main/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17&Itemid=34 |title=The Top Talk Radio Audiences |accessdate=2008-12-18 |date=November 2008 |publisher=[[Talkers magazine]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080324045418/http://www.talkers.com/main/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17&Itemid=34 |archivedate=2008-03-24 }}</ref>\n\nRamsey takes live calls on the theme of finance, and occasionally money-related Christian philosophy as it pertains to [[Tithe|tithing]], etc.  During the show, he discusses life and money-related issues with callers. He is known for his complete disdain of [[debt collector]]s, calling them (among other things) \"scum\" and dishonest, and urging his listeners not to deal with them unless necessary, and then to get everything in writing, especially involving offers to reduce debts.\n\nWith a simple, seven-stage \"baby steps\" formula (Baby Step Two is based on the [[debt snowball method]]), Ramsey urges listeners to avoid all [[debt]] except for certain types of home [[mortgages]].\n\nRamsey's Seven Baby Steps are:\n\n1. Save $1,000 for a starter emergency fund.\n\n2. Pay off all debt (except the house) using the debt snowball.\n\n3. Save 3-6 months expenses in a fully funded emergency fund.\n\n4. Invest 15% of household income in retirement.\n\n5. Save for children's college fund.\n\n6. Pay off home early.\n\n7. Build wealth and give.\n\nOne notable difference between his and other financial shows is that Ramsey attempts to go beyond mathematical mechanics and reach his callers on an emotional and spiritual level.<ref name=\"Radio Ink Industry Q&A\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.radioink.com/listingsEntry.asp?ID=468144&PT=industryqa|title=Dave Ramsey: Money in the Bank (10/02/06)|accessdate=2006-12-03|publisher=Radio Ink|year=2006|author=Joe Howard, Editor-In-Chief}}</ref>\n\nThe show has a channel on [[iHeartRadio]].<ref name=iheartdaveramsey>{{cite web|title=Dave Ramsey Channel|url=http://www.iheart.com/live/dave-ramsey-channel-5859/|website=[[iHeartRadio]]|publisher=[[iHeartMedia, Inc.]]|accessdate=20 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe program began June 15, 1992, when Ramsey, selling copies of ''Financial Peace'' out of the trunk of his car, was a guest on 99.7 [[WWTN]].<ref name=\"Company History\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.daveramsey.com/etc/cms/index.cfm?intContentID=2797|title=Our Company History|accessdate=2006-12-03|publisher=daveramsey.com|year=2006|author=Dave Ramsey |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061018173517/http://www.daveramsey.com/etc/cms/index.cfm?intContentID=2797 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2006-10-18}}</ref>  The station had recently filed Chapter 11 bankruptcy and one of its hosts had quit after not getting paid, which left the station scrambling to fill the gap in its lineup. Ramsey offered to do a one-hour show for free for one month, not entirely expecting to be successful. ''The Money Game'' went on the air with Ramsey,<ref name=\"About Us\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.daveramsey.com/etc/cms/about_us_2932.htmlc|title=About us|accessdate=2006-12-03|publisher=daveramsey.com|year=2006|author=Dave Ramsey}}</ref> Hal Wilson<ref name=\"Hal Wilson\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.wilsongrouprealestate.com/hal.html|title=The Wilson Group Real Estate|accessdate=2006-12-03|publisher=Wilson Group Real Estate|author=Hal Wilson |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070308095638/http://www.wilsongrouprealestate.com/hal.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-03-08}}</ref> and Roy Matlock<ref name=\"About Nashville DR\">{{Cite web|url=http://nashville.about.com/cs/famousresidents/a/daveramsey_3.htm|title=The Money Game|accessdate=2006-12-03|publisher=About Nashville, TN|author=Jan Duke}}</ref> each hosting the hour alone on certain days of the week. Ramsey was the bankruptcy and \"get out of debt\" guru on Mondays and Wednesdays, Matlock answered investing questions Tuesdays and Thursdays, and Wilson's Friday topic was primarily real estate. After station management asked Wilson to discontinue his portion of the program, Ramsey and Matlock teamed up to host the show five days per week. Eventually, Matlock left the show on good terms to focus on his financial services business, leaving Ramsey to host the show alone.\n\nThe program became quite popular in Nashville. Reportedly, when WWTN asked Ramsey who would be syndicating his show, Ramsey simply pointed to Blake Thompson, who continues as executive producer of the show to this day. As Bill Hampton, Vice President of The Lampo Group stated, \"they learned syndication from the ground up.\"<ref name=\"Inside Radio\">{{Cite web|url=http://ftp.media.radcity.net/ZMST/daily/IS032405.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050514181128/http://ftp.media.radcity.net/ZMST/daily/IS032405.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=2005-05-14|title=The Inside Story with Mike Kinosian: Behind The Dave Ramsey Show|accessdate=2006-12-03|publisher=InsideRadio.com|year=2005|author=Mike Kinosian|format=PDF}}</ref>\n\n''The Money Game'' changed its name to ''The Dave Ramsey Show'' in mid-1996.<ref name=\"GRI\">{{cite book | title=Financial Peace Revisited| last=Ramsey| first=Dave|author2=Sharon Ramsey | year=2003| pages=Preface, x| publisher=Viking Penguin| location=Harmondsworth, Middlesex, England| id=0-670-03208-5}}</ref> As of 2017, the show is heard on more than 585 stations.<ref name=\"Ramsey Media Relations\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.daveramsey.com/press-release/2017-marks-the-25th-anniversary-of-the-dave-ramsey-show|title=\"2017 MARKS THE 25th ANNIVERSARY OF \u201cTHE DAVE RAMSEY SHOW|accessdate=2017-05-08|publisher=daveramsey.com|year=2017|author=Beth Tallent}}</ref> In 2006, the show received two nominations for the 2006 Radio & Records News/Talk Industry Achievement Awards. It is the fifth year in a row for Dave Ramsey in the \"Syndicated Personality of the Year\" category, and the second year in a row for Bill Hampton in the \"Executive of the Year\" category.<ref name=\"Tallent\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.daveramsey.com/etc/cms/index.cfm?intContentID=4360|title=\"THE DAVE RAMSEY SHOW\" RECEIVES TWO NOMINATIONS IN THE 2006 RADIO & RECORDS NEWS/TALK INDUSTRY ACHIEVEMENT AWARDS|accessdate=2006-12-03|publisher=daveramsey.com|year=2006|author=Beth Tallent |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060630212716/http://www.daveramsey.com/etc/cms/index.cfm?intContentID=4360 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2006-06-30}}</ref>\n\nOn the success of the show, Bill Hampton stated that it did $2.5 million in network sales in 2005 while MyTMMO.com did $1.2 million. He also stated the show would bring in an estimated $3.7 million from advertisers.<ref name=\"Inside Radio\"/>  The show is now also available on [[podcast]] via [[iTunes Store|iTunes]].\n\nRamsey's show is one of very few national radio shows to be [[Radio syndication|self-syndicated]]. The program is not connected to any national network or programming service, and is distributed directly to local stations. Ramsey's show is fed to stations 24/7 so that stations will not have to record his show for later broadcast, but rather they can always use the satellite feed. The show is distributed via [[Westwood One (current)|Westwood One]]'s satellite platform.\n\nAfter 20 years of broadcasting on WTN, on January 1, 2013, the show moved to 102.5 FM (''\"The Game\"''). Ramsey and WTN were unable to come to terms over a renewal contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wsmv.com/story/20317565/financial-guru-dave-ramsey-leaving-997-after-20-years|title=Financial guru Dave Ramsey leaving 99.7 after 20 years|publisher=WSMV Nashville, TN|date=December 11, 2012|accessdate=July 30, 2013}}</ref> One year later, on January 1, 2014, the show moved to [[WLAC]].\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.daveramsey.com Dave Ramsey] - Official site\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dave Ramsey Show, The (radio)}}\n[[Category:Radio programs on XM Satellite Radio]]\n[[Category:American talk radio programs]]\n[[Category:Media in Nashville, Tennessee]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the TV program|The Dave Ramsey Show (TV program)}}\n{{Infobox Radio Show\n| show_name          = The Dave Ramsey Show\n| image              = \n| imagesize          = \n| caption            =\n| format             = Financial talk\n| runtime            = 3 hours per episode\n| creator            = [[Dave Ramsey]]\n| writer             = \n| executive_producer = Blake Thompson\n| starring           = [[Dave Ramsey]]\n| opentheme          = \"[[Baker Street (song)|Baker Street]]\" by [[Gerry Rafferty]]\n| endtheme           = \"[[Money (Pink Floyd song)|Money]]\" by [[Pink Floyd]]\n| country            = {{flagicon|United States}} [[United States]]\n| first_aired        = 1992\n| last_aired         = present\n| num_episodes       = \n| website            = http://www.daveramsey.com/radio\n| home_station       = 1510 [[WLAC]]\n| podcast\t     = \n}}\n\n'''The Dave Ramsey Show''' is a three-hour, [[Radio syndication|self-syndicated]] radio program and podcast, hosted by the [[Dave Ramsey|eponymous finance author and speaker]], that airs Monday through Friday from 2-5 PM [[Eastern Time Zone|ET]]. It is primarily broadcast from [[Brentwood, Tennessee]], though often during the summer it is broadcast via remote from Ramsey's lake house.<ref name=\"Axia Interview: Blake Thompson\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.axiaaudio.com/interviews/features/ramsey.htm|title=Axia Interview with Blake Thompson, producer of The Dave Ramsey Show|accessdate=2006-12-03|publisher=www.axiaaudio.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070313071456/http://www.axiaaudio.com/interviews/features/ramsey.htm|archivedate=2007-03-13}}</ref> {{As of|2008}}, it is one of the top ten [[List of most-listened-to radio programs|most-listened-to radio shows]].<ref name=talkers2008>{{cite news |url=http://www.talkers.com/main/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17&Itemid=34 |title=The Top Talk Radio Audiences |accessdate=2008-12-18 |date=November 2008 |publisher=[[Talkers magazine]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080324045418/http://www.talkers.com/main/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=17&Itemid=34 |archivedate=2008-03-24 }}</ref>\n\nRamsey takes live calls on the theme of finance, and occasionally money-related Christian philosophy as it pertains to [[Tithe|tithing]], etc.  During the show, he discusses life and money-related issues with callers. He is known for his complete disdain of [[debt collector]]s, calling them (among other things) \"scum\" and dishonest, and urging his listeners not to deal with them unless necessary, and then to get everything in writing, especially involving offers to reduce debts.\n\nWith a simple, seven-stage \"baby steps\" formula (based in part on the [[debt snowball method]]), Ramsey urges listeners to avoid all [[debt]] except for certain types of home [[mortgages]], and to invest conservatively in timeshares and digital currency.\n\nOne notable difference between his and other financial shows is that Ramsey attempts to go beyond mathematical mechanics and reach his callers on an emotional and spiritual level.<ref name=\"Radio Ink Industry Q&A\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.radioink.com/listingsEntry.asp?ID=468144&PT=industryqa|title=Dave Ramsey: Money in the Bank (10/02/06)|accessdate=2006-12-03|publisher=Radio Ink|year=2006|author=Joe Howard, Editor-In-Chief}}</ref>\n\nThe show has a channel on [[iHeartRadio]].<ref name=iheartdaveramsey>{{cite web|title=Dave Ramsey Channel|url=http://www.iheart.com/live/dave-ramsey-channel-5859/|website=[[iHeartRadio]]|publisher=[[iHeartMedia, Inc.]]|accessdate=20 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe program began June 15, 1992, when Ramsey, selling copies of ''Financial Peace'' out of the trunk of his car, was a guest on 99.7 [[WWTN]].<ref name=\"Company History\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.daveramsey.com/etc/cms/index.cfm?intContentID=2797|title=Our Company History|accessdate=2006-12-03|publisher=daveramsey.com|year=2006|author=Dave Ramsey |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061018173517/http://www.daveramsey.com/etc/cms/index.cfm?intContentID=2797 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2006-10-18}}</ref>  The station had recently filed Chapter 11 bankruptcy and one of its hosts had quit after not getting paid, which left the station scrambling to fill the gap in its lineup. Ramsey offered to do a one-hour show for free for one month, not entirely expecting to be successful. ''The Money Game'' went on the air with Ramsey,<ref name=\"About Us\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.daveramsey.com/etc/cms/about_us_2932.htmlc|title=About us|accessdate=2006-12-03|publisher=daveramsey.com|year=2006|author=Dave Ramsey}}</ref> Hal Wilson<ref name=\"Hal Wilson\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.wilsongrouprealestate.com/hal.html|title=The Wilson Group Real Estate|accessdate=2006-12-03|publisher=Wilson Group Real Estate|author=Hal Wilson |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070308095638/http://www.wilsongrouprealestate.com/hal.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-03-08}}</ref> and Roy Matlock<ref name=\"About Nashville DR\">{{Cite web|url=http://nashville.about.com/cs/famousresidents/a/daveramsey_3.htm|title=The Money Game|accessdate=2006-12-03|publisher=About Nashville, TN|author=Jan Duke}}</ref> each hosting the hour alone on certain days of the week. Ramsey was the bankruptcy and \"get out of debt\" guru on Mondays and Wednesdays, Matlock answered investing questions Tuesdays and Thursdays, and Wilson's Friday topic was primarily real estate. After station management asked Wilson to discontinue his portion of the program, Ramsey and Matlock teamed up to host the show five days per week. Eventually, Matlock left the show on good terms to focus on his financial services business, leaving Ramsey to host the show alone.\n\nThe program became quite popular in Nashville. Reportedly, when WWTN asked Ramsey who would be syndicating his show, Ramsey simply pointed to Blake Thompson, who continues as executive producer of the show to this day. As Bill Hampton, Vice President of The Lampo Group stated, \"they learned syndication from the ground up.\"<ref name=\"Inside Radio\">{{Cite web|url=http://ftp.media.radcity.net/ZMST/daily/IS032405.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050514181128/http://ftp.media.radcity.net/ZMST/daily/IS032405.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=2005-05-14|title=The Inside Story with Mike Kinosian: Behind The Dave Ramsey Show|accessdate=2006-12-03|publisher=InsideRadio.com|year=2005|author=Mike Kinosian|format=PDF}}</ref>\n\n''The Money Game'' changed its name to ''The Dave Ramsey Show'' in mid-1996.<ref name=\"GRI\">{{cite book | title=Financial Peace Revisited| last=Ramsey| first=Dave|author2=Sharon Ramsey | year=2003| pages=Preface, x| publisher=Viking Penguin| location=Harmondsworth, Middlesex, England| id=0-670-03208-5}}</ref> As of 2017, the show is heard on more than 585 stations.<ref name=\"Ramsey Media Relations\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.daveramsey.com/press-release/2017-marks-the-25th-anniversary-of-the-dave-ramsey-show|title=\"2017 MARKS THE 25th ANNIVERSARY OF \u201cTHE DAVE RAMSEY SHOW|accessdate=2017-05-08|publisher=daveramsey.com|year=2017|author=Beth Tallent}}</ref> In 2006, the show received two nominations for the 2006 Radio & Records News/Talk Industry Achievement Awards. It is the fifth year in a row for Dave Ramsey in the \"Syndicated Personality of the Year\" category, and the second year in a row for Bill Hampton in the \"Executive of the Year\" category.<ref name=\"Tallent\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.daveramsey.com/etc/cms/index.cfm?intContentID=4360|title=\"THE DAVE RAMSEY SHOW\" RECEIVES TWO NOMINATIONS IN THE 2006 RADIO & RECORDS NEWS/TALK INDUSTRY ACHIEVEMENT AWARDS|accessdate=2006-12-03|publisher=daveramsey.com|year=2006|author=Beth Tallent |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060630212716/http://www.daveramsey.com/etc/cms/index.cfm?intContentID=4360 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2006-06-30}}</ref>\n\nOn the success of the show, Bill Hampton stated that it did $2.5 million in network sales in 2005 while MyTMMO.com did $1.2 million. He also stated the show would bring in an estimated $3.7 million from advertisers.<ref name=\"Inside Radio\"/>  The show is now also available on [[podcast]] via [[iTunes Store|iTunes]].\n\nRamsey's show is one of very few national radio shows to be [[Radio syndication|self-syndicated]]. The program is not connected to any national network or programming service, and is distributed directly to local stations. Ramsey's show is fed to stations 24/7 so that stations will not have to record his show for later broadcast, but rather they can always use the satellite feed. The show is distributed via [[Westwood One (current)|Westwood One]]'s satellite platform.\n\nAfter 20 years of broadcasting on WTN, on January 1, 2013, the show moved to 102.5 FM (''\"The Game\"''). Ramsey and WTN were unable to come to terms over a renewal contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wsmv.com/story/20317565/financial-guru-dave-ramsey-leaving-997-after-20-years|title=Financial guru Dave Ramsey leaving 99.7 after 20 years|publisher=WSMV Nashville, TN|date=December 11, 2012|accessdate=July 30, 2013}}</ref> One year later, on January 1, 2014, the show moved to [[WLAC]].\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.daveramsey.com Dave Ramsey] - Official site\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dave Ramsey Show, The (radio)}}\n[[Category:Radio programs on XM Satellite Radio]]\n[[Category:American talk radio programs]]\n[[Category:Media in Nashville, Tennessee]]\n", "name_user": "Megan.McConnell", "label": "safe", "comment": "What The Dave Ramsey Show recommends for the 7 Baby Steps was incorrect in this listing, so I've updated it with a link to the Ramsey Baby Steps.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Dave_Ramsey_Show_(radio_program)"}
